NAME: P. Crowley
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace six-bay two-storey house, built c. 1790.  Timber shopfront inserted, c. 1900, to left hand side.  Now also in use as public house.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Lime-washed walls.  Shopfront comprising timber pilasters flanking tripartite fixed window and timber panelled doors with overlights, having fascia, marbleised lettering and cornice above.  Timber panelled door with overlight to right hand side.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.  Steps leading to entrance door.  Stone kerbing to footpath.  Attached single-bay single-storey lean-to outbuilding to left.

NAME: Corrofin Bridge
COMPOSITION: Triple-arch hump-back road bridge over River Fergus, built c. 1790, with rubble stone walls, cut-stone voussoirs, coursed rubble buttresses and V-cutwaters.

NAME: Richmond House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1800, prostyle diastyle Doric portico added, c. 1840.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks, gabled dormer windows and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with render quoins.  Round-headed door opening having cut-granite Gibbsian door surround with fluted keystone.  Timber panelled and glazed double leaf doors with radial fanlight.  Timber sliding sash window.  Timber casement windows to dormers.  Cobbled yard to rear.  Detached four-bay two-storey rubble stone coach house with dormer attic, built c. 1790, having lunette window openings to first floor.  Extensively renovated and subdivided, c. 1995, to accommodate use as apartments.  Remains of detached single-bay two-storey rubble stone building, now in ruins.  Cut-stone gate piers with obelisk pinnacles.

NAME: Sean Kenny and Sons
COMPOSITION: Attached six-bay two-storey market house set on raised plinth, built 1876, incorporating fabric of earlier building, c. 1700.  Two-bay two-storey extension added to rear, c. 1985.  Pitched Moher flagged roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Single-pitched corrugated-iron roof to extension.  Rendered walls with cut-stone plinth and buttresses.  Inset crest and date plaque to front elevation.  Three round-headed openings to ground floor and square-headed openings to first floor, all with replacement timber windows.

NAME: Saint Brigid's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1822, with three-bay gable front and two-bay nave.  Two-bay single-storey sacristy added to rear, c. 1995, with inset archaeological fragment to exterior wall.  Pitched artificial slate roof with bellcote over entrance gable having cross finial, moulded gable copings and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Snecked stone walls with cut-stone quoins, niche to gable and blind openings flanking entrance door.  Rendered walls to transepts.  Four-centred arch door opening with timber sheeted double leaf doors, fanlight and label moulding.  Lancet window openings, set in tripartite arrangement over entrance door.  Replacement uPVC windows.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-stone gate piers set in rubble stone walls to site.

NAME: Clare Heritage Centre
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Church of Ireland church, built c. 1715, comprising four-bay double-height nave, with single-bay three-stage entrance tower and spire and single-bay single-storey vestry, added 1829.  Two-bay single-storey wing added, 1979-1982, to accommodate use as heritage centre.  Pitched slate roof with profile stone copings.  Needle spire and pinnacles to tower.  Rendered walls, render quoins and render architraves to nave.  Snecked limestone walls with corner buttresses, string courses and cut-stone window dressings to tower.  Carved memorial stone plaque beside door to extension.  Pointed arch door opening with timber doors and carved hood moulding.  Lancet windows with timber sliding sash windows.  Tripartite lancet chancel window with leaded stained glass.  Retaining interior features including marble memorials, timber pulpit, chancel arch and panelled gallery.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers.  Cut-stone piers to site.

NAME: Cahirs
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1870, timber pubfront inserted, c. 1920.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking fixed window and timber panelled half glazed door with fascia and moulded cornice above.  Timber panelled door with overlight.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.  Thick stone flag forms bridge over drain in footpath to front.

NAME: Studdert Mausoleum
COMPOSITION: Freestanding single-bay single-storey part-sunken granite cut-stone Studdert family mausoleum, built c. 1820.  Recessed central cast-iron door flanked by engaged columns, approached by flight of steps and with inscribed plaque above.  Stepped pyramidal roof.

NAME: O'Connell Monument
COMPOSITION: Monument to Daniel O'Connell, erected 1867, in the form of a Roman Doric column set on a square-plan base having inset panels and surmounted with a limestone statue of a cloaked figure with raised hand facing up O'Connell Street.  The statue stands on a drum decorated with a scroll of shamrocks.  Set on the site of former courthouse, demolished 1852.

NAME: Bank of Ireland
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited ten-bay three-storey purpose-built bank and bank manager's house, built 1874, with entrance bay set in curved corner.  Main façade comprises two-bays on each street flanking the entrance bay.  Five-bay block forms a subsidiary block along Bank Place.  Pitched slate roof.  Cut-limestone walls to ground floor, having cut-limestone pilasters with capitals and scrolls above, flanking the main façade openings.  Red brick walls to upper floors.  Limestone cornice and string courses between floors.  Timber panelled door and overlight set in recessed opening.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Segmental-arched openings to ground floor.  Square-headed openings with limestone architraves to first floor, having segmental pediments to main façade openings.  Segmental-arched openings to second floor with limestone architraves.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Bank of Ireland
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey bank and bank manager’s house, built 1864, with three-bay central breakfront flanked by recessed entrance bays.  Hipped slate roof with cut stone chimneystacks having chamfered edges.  Cut-limestone walls with quoins to accentuating corners and breakfront, cut-stone pilasters flanking ground floor windows and carved colonnettes flanking entrance doors.  Dentillated string course between floors.  Bracketed eaves course.  Round-headed openings to ground floor with billeted carved detail to archivolts.  Timber sliding sash windows to breakfront.  Timber panelled doors with plain fanlights.  Shouldered square-headed openings to first floor with timber sliding sash windows.

End-of-terrace two-bay three-storey over part-raised basement Victorian house, built c. 1865, with rectangular bay-window to ground floor and basement.  Built as part of a terrace of four houses.  Hipped slate roof with bracketed eaves and large chimneystack having yellow brick banding.  Red brick walls with yellow brick quoins, string courses and keystones.  Limestone walls to basement.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber door with overlight.  Limestone steps leading to entrance door.  Wrought-iron railings to steps and basement area.  Coach house to rear.

Terraced two-bay three-storey over part raised basement Victorian house, built c. 1865, with rectangular bay-window to ground floor and basement.  Built as part of a terrace of four houses.  Pitched slate roof with bracketed eaves and large chimneystack having yellow brick banding.  Red brick walls with yellow brick quoins, string courses and keystones.  Limestone walls to basement.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber door with overlight.  Limestone steps leading to entrance door.  Wrought-iron railings to steps and basement area.  Coach house to rear.

Terraced two-bay three-storey over part raised basement Victorian house, built c. 1865, with rectangular bay-window to ground floor and basement.  Built as part of a terrace of four houses.  Pitched slate roof with bracketed eaves and large chimneystack having yellow brick banding.  Red brick walls with yellow brick quoins, string courses and keystones.  Limestone walls to basement.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber door with overlight.  Limestone steps leading to entrance door.  Wrought-iron railings to steps and basement area.  Coach house to rear.

End-of-terrace two-bay three-storey over part raised basement Victorian house, built c. 1865, with rectangular bay-window to ground floor and basement.  Built as part of a terrace of four houses.  Hipped slate roof with bracketed eaves and large chimneystack having yellow brick banding.  Red brick walls with yellow brick quoins, string courses and keystones.  Limestone walls to basement.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber door with overlight.  Limestone steps leading to entrance door.  Wrought-iron railings to steps and basement area.  Coach house to rear.
Multiple-bay two and three-storey commercial  building, built c. 1875, with red brick facade over high shopfront having plaster cornice and fascia boards, c. 1920.

NAME: Allied Irish Bank
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey bank and manager’s house, built 1916, with advanced end bays.  Hipped slate roof with large brick chimney stacks and cut stone moulded cornices.  Channelled limestone walls to ground floor with rope moulding in string course at ground floor sill level.  Panelled brickwork to upper floors, with carved limestone stringcourse, cut-stone piers of raised quoins having swags to capitals, frieze cornice and blocking cornice.  Round-headed openings to ground floor.  Square-headed openings to upper floors with limestone lintels.

NAME: Saint Columba's Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding asymmetrical-plan French-Gothic style Church of Ireland church, dated 1871. Architect W.H.Lynn. Comprising wide nave with polygonal apse, equally wide north aisle, bell tower on north side and entrance porch on north side.  Pitched roof roofs with finials on gables.  Chimneystack for heating system shaped as round tower.  Saddleback roof to tower.  Rusticated limestone walls.  Paired lancet windows set in block-and-start dressed stone surrounds.  Lancet door opening to porch with short colonnettes having foliated stone capitals resting on plinths.  Open king post roof and lancet arches with foliate capitals to interior.  Retaining interior features including organ, added 1873, low arcaded reredos painted by Brigid Ganley and ceramic figures of saints by C. O’Brien, c. 1925.  Built on site donated by the Bindon Blood Family.

NAME: Allied Irish Bank
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey Italianate-style bank and manager’s house, built 1864, with advanced single-storey entrance porch addition.  Two-storey hip-roofed side entrance extension to right.  Hipped slate roof with paired limestone stone brackets under moulded limestone eaves course.  Cut stone decoration to chimneystacks.  Limestone cut-stone walls with string courses at sill levels.  Gibbsian door surround flanked by engaged pilasters with moulded cornice above to porch.  Round-headed openings with roll mouldings and dropped keystones to ground floor.  Segmental-arched openings with architrave and dropped keystone to first floor.  Round-headed door opening to side entrance.  Timber sash windows and timber panelled doors to openings.

End-of-terrace two-bay four-storey over basement Georgian-style former townhouse, built 1832, now in use as office.  Built as part of a terrace of six houses.  Pitched slate roof with stone coping to parapet.  Red brick walls.  Plastered walls to gable.  Timber panelled door flanked by engaged fluted columns with moulded lintel and wrought-iron cobweb fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Flight of limestone steps leading to entrance door.  Cast-iron railings to steps and basement area.  Yard to rear.

Terraced two-bay four-storey over basement Georgian-style former townhouse, built 1832, now in use as office.  Built as part of a terrace of six houses.  Pitched slate roof with stone coping to parapet.  Red brick walls.  Timber panelled door flanked by engaged fluted columns with moulded lintel and wrought-iron cobweb fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Flight of limestone steps leading to entrance door.  Cast-iron railings to steps and basement area.  Yard to rear.

Terraced two-bay four-storey over basement Georgian-style former townhouse, built 1832, now in use as office.  Built as part of a terrace of six houses.  Pitched slate roof with downpipe to centre of facade.  Channelled render walls to ground floor.  Roughcast rendered walls to upper floors with render quoins.  Timber panelled door flanked by engaged fluted columns with moulded lintel and wrought-iron cobweb fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows with moulded lintels to upper floors.  Flight of limestone steps leading to entrance door.  Cast-iron railings to steps and basement area.  Yard to rear.

Terraced two-bay four-storey over basement Georgian-style former townhouse, built 1832, now in use as office.  Built as part of a terrace of six houses.  Pitched slate roof with downpipe to centre of facade.  Channelled render walls to ground floor.  Roughcast rendered walls to upper floors with render quoins.  Timber panelled door flanked by engaged fluted columns with moulded lintel and wrought-iron cobweb fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows with moulded lintels to upper floors.  Flight of limestone steps leading to entrance door.  Cast-iron railings to steps and basement area.  Yard to rear.

Terraced two-bay four-storey over basement Georgian-style former townhouse, built 1834, now in use as office.  Built as part of a terrace of six houses.  Pitched slate roof with stone coping to parapet.  Red brick walls.  Timber panelled door flanked by engaged fluted columns with moulded lintel and wrought-iron cobweb fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Flight of limestone steps leading to entrance door.  Cast-iron railings to steps and basement area.  Yard to rear.

End-of-terrace two-bay four-storey over basement Georgian-style townhouse, built c. 1835.  Bay window added to ground floor and two-bay single-storey extension to left, c. 1850.  Built as part of a terrace of six houses.  Pitched slate roof with stone coping to parapet.  Red brick walls.  Limestone quoins to extension.  Pedimented limestone doorcase, added c. 1850.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Flight of limestone steps leading to entrance door.  Retaining interior features.  Cast-iron railings to steps and basement area.  Yard to rear.

End-of-terrace two-bay three-storey over basement Georgian style former townhouse, built c. 1835, as part of a terrace of five houses.  Now in use as offices.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Red brick walls.  Timber panelled door flanked by pilasters with radial fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Cast-iron railings surrounding basement area.  Outbuildings to rear.

Terraced two-bay three-storey over basement Georgian style former townhouse, built c. 1835, as part of a terrace of five houses.  Now in use as offices.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Red brick walls.  Timber panelled door flanked by pilasters with radial fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Cast-iron railings surrounding basement area.  Outbuildings to rear.

Terraced two-bay three-storey over basement Georgian style former townhouse, built c. 1835, as part of a terrace of five houses.  Now in use as offices.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Red brick walls.  Timber panelled door flanked by pilasters with radial fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Cast-iron railings surrounding basement area.  Outbuildings to rear.

Terraced two-bay three-storey over basement Georgian style former townhouse, built c. 1835, as part of a terrace of five houses.  Now in use as offices.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and dormer window additions.  Red brick walls.  Timber panelled door flanked by pilasters with radial fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Cast-iron railings surrounding basement area.  Outbuildings to rear.

End-of-terrace two-bay three-storey over basement Georgian style former townhouse, built c. 1835, as part of a terrace of five houses.  Now in use as offices.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and dormer window additions.  Red brick walls.  Timber panelled door flanked by pilasters with radial fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Cast-iron railings surrounding basement area.  Outbuildings to rear.

NAME: Bindon House
COMPOSITION: Attached three-bay three-storey former house over basement, built c. 1845, now in use as office.  Hipped artificial slate roof.  Roughly coursed dressed limestone walls with quoins.  Cut stone door surround with cornice above, having timber panelled door and overlight.  Timber sliding sash windows with cut-limestone block-and-start surrounds.  Cast-iron railings to basement area.  Cut stone door surround and rubble stone wall to former garden to right.

NAME: Belle-view House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey former house, built c. 1820, now in use as county library headquarters.  Large wing added to rear.  Hipped slate roof with two centrally placed rendered chimneystacks.  Roughly coursed rubble stone walls.  Timber sliding sash windows with brick dressings to openings.  Timber panelled door flanked by pilasters with moulded cornice and fanlight having wrought-iron decorative detail above.  Low castellated coursed stone wall added to site.

NAME: De Valera Library and Museum
COMPOSITION: Freestanding single cell Gothic Revival former Presbyterian church, built c. 1855 to design by Joseph Fogarty.  Remodelled, 1975, to accommodate use as museum.  Pitched slate roof with finials to gables and cut stone chimneystack to west.  Cut-limestone walls to gable and rendered walls to sides, all with cut stone plinth and buttresses.  Pointed arch openings to entrance gable with moulded hood mouldings.  Altered openings to sides, comprising tall, narrow square-headed window openings.

Detached irregular-plan multiple-bay three-storey building of three periods, commenced c. 1780.  Originally built as house, later used as clubhouse.  Comprising three-bay three-storey main block with adjoining two-bay three-storey block, having wing set at right angle to main elevation, and with mid nineteenth century bow-fronted extension to river side elevation.  Pitched and hipped slate roofs with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with string course and quoins.  Heavy cornice and frieze around bow fronted extension.  Entrance porch to main block comprising Ionic columns set in chamfered corners with broken pediment above.  Pair of bay windows to river elevation.  Timber sliding sash and some replacement aluminium windows.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Clare Music Education Centre
COMPOSITION: Detached multiple-bay three-storey over basement school, built c.1775.  Used as Erasmus Smith Academy until 1888.  In use as Ordnance Survey office into the 1920s.  Purchased by Sisters of Mercy in 1941.  Steeply pitched roof with four large rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with decorative pediment additions added to ground floor by Edward F. Ryan in 1941.  Square-headed openings and pair of round-headed openings over entrance door, all with timber sliding sash windows.  Round-head door opening flanked by sidelights and approached by flight of steps.  Retaining interior features.  Octagonal-profile gate piers support simple wrought-iron gates and railing.  Carefully sited closing vista of College Road.

NAME: Ennis Courthouse
COMPOSITION: Freestanding multiple-bay two-storey courthouse over basement, built 1852 to design attributed to J.B.Keane and Henry Whitestone.  Comprising pedimented Ionic hexastyle portico approached by nine steps and surrounded by balustrade, flanked by three-bay blocks with advanced end bays.  Hipped slate roofs.  Cyclopean rusticated limestone to basement.  Cut-limestone to remaining floors with carved cornices, frieze, capitals and pediment.  Centrally placed main entrance with carved limestone bracketed cornice and architrave.  Side entrances with carved limestone pediments.  Carved limestone pediments and lintels with scrolls over end bay openings.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features including marble statue of Michael O’ Loghlen (1789-1842), Master of Rolls in Ireland, by J. R. Kirk, RHA.  Single-storey extension, faced in machine cut stone, with blue aluminium framing glazed entrance bay, designed by Dermot and Sean Merry.  Occupying imposing site on a slight rise with terrace in front, park below, and gun from Crimean War on lawn to left of building.

NAME: Abbeyfield House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay three-storey house, built c. 1750, having three-storey wings and connecting bay to further three-storey section, all to rear.  Salient two-story wing to right, c. 1820.  Two-storey extension, c. 1900 to rear.  Pitched slate roof with red brick stacks to gables.  Pitched slate roofs to rear sections.  Hipped slate roof to salient wing.  Roughcast rendered walls with eaves cornice.  Rendered walls to salient wing.  Roughly coursed rubble stone walls to rear with some roughcast render and lime wash in places.  Shouldered architrave with scroll keystone surmounted by pediment supported by consoles to front door.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Set on bend of the river.  Terminates the vista of Abbey Street to the north.  Large stable block close to river bank, possibly suggesting former military use.

NAME: New Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch road bridge over river, built c. 1835, with rusticated voussoirs.  Original stone parapet replaced with cement piers and metal railings.

NAME: The Cloister Restaurant
COMPOSITION: Detached multiple-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1650, with battered gable end addressing street, three-bay two-storey wing to north at slight angle, possibly eighteenth century in date, and having late nineteenth century three-bay single-storey wing with attic accommodation to south.  In use as coach factory in 1841.  Now in use as restaurant and public house.  Pitched slate roofs with rendered and red brick chimneystacks.  Floating pediment to rear, possibly remaining part of demolished wing.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflights to south wing.  Battered rendered walls with quoins to street elevation.  Rendered walls to flanking wings.  Projecting slated canopy over ground floor openings.  Roughcast rendered walls to rear.  Replacement fittings to openings.  Retaining interior features.  Built on site of old Friary.

NAME: Franciscan Abbey
COMPOSITION: Franciscan Abbey, founded c. 1240, now in ruins. National Monument in care of the Office of Public Works

Corner-sited five-bay two-storey former house with attic accommodation, built c. 1650, now in use as commercial outlets.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflights.  Very fine diagonally placed stone chimneystacks.  Coping stone line in stacks indicates roof pitch has been lowered.  Rendered and roughcast rendered walls with slight kink to front façade.  Walls appear very thick.  Segmental-arched openings to first floor, with replacement timber sash and casement windows.  Square-headed openings to ground floor with various replacement fittings.  Late nineteenth century shopfront comprising fixed windows with central glazing bar and glazed spandrels, flanked by pilasters and with cornice above.

NAME: O'Connell's Medical Hall
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1800, as a pair with the adjoining house.  Now in use as retail outlet.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Rendered walls with render quoins.  Late nineteenth century projecting shopfront with curved end and moulded cornice.  Chrome framed fixed windows and lettering inserted to shopfront c. 1940.  Timber sliding sash windows set in moulded architraves.

Corner-sited end-of-terrace two-bay four-storey house, built c.1775, now also in use as retail outlet.  Remains of eighteenth century stonework of former courthouse to gable wall.  Courthouse demolished mid nineteenth century.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Rendered and roughcast rendered walls.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Early twentieth- century shopfront to ground floor with fine quatrefoils in caps of pilasters.

NAME: Saint Mary's Franciscan Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted Victorian Roman Catholic church, built c. 1885, with tower to west, polygonal apse and connecting block leading to friary.  Pitched slate roofs with gable finials.  Snecked limestone walls with cut-stone quoins, buttresses between window openings and projecting confessional additions.  Statue of the Blessed Virgin Mary set in niche and flanked by lancet windows having stone tracery, with quatrefoil and hood moulding above.  Group repeated on smaller scale to gable apex.  Paired lancet windows set between buttresses.  Arcade of lancet windows with carved labels stops to connecting block.  Diagonally sheeted timber double leaf doors with wrought-iron strap hinges, flanked by pairs of polished granite colonnettes with foliated capitals, having pediment above with inset pointed overlight having carved stone foil.  Form of main entrance repeated on smaller scale for side entrances.  Open timber roof with tongue and groove sheeting behind to interior.  Four polished granite columns with carved stylised ivy capital divide nave from transepts.  Stained glass by Early.  Cast-iron railings and polygonal gate piers to site.  Foundation stone of earlier church on site set in grotto to the east.

NAME: The Friary
COMPOSITION: Attached L-plan three-storey friary, built 1877, adjoining Franciscan church to north.  Pitched slate roof with some artificial slate patches, rendered chimneystacks having moulded cornices and wide eaves brackets.  Snecked limestone walls with cut-stone quoins and block-and-start surrounds to segmental-arched openings.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Built on the site of eighteenth century Willowbank House and may incorporate some fabric of this earlier building.

Terraced single-bay three-storey house, built c. 1775, as a pair with the adjoining house to the left.  Retail outlet inserted to ground floor.  Pitched slate roof.  Thick walls with roughcast render.  Timber sliding sash windows to upper floors, having stone sill to first floor and brick sill to second floor.  Early twentieth century shopfront to ground floor comprising pilasters flanking timber fixed windows and timber panelled door with fascia, simple consoles and cornice above.  Set on narrow eighteenth century street.

End-of-terrace two-bay two-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1790, retaining fabric of seventeenth century building.  Timber shopfront, c. 1900, to ground floor.  Pitched artificial slate roof with large seventeenth century stone chimneystack having three diagonally placed stone pots.  Stone coping on chimneystack indicates roof pitch was higher.  Rendered walls with render quoins and moulded eaves course to front elevation.  Rubble stone walls to gable, very thick and now bowed, probably contemporary with chimneystack.  Timber sliding sash windows and timber panelled door to gable.  Timber sliding sash windows with raised reveals and sills to first floor.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking openings with fascia and cornice above.  Set on corner of narrow eighteenth century street.

Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1850, renovated c. 1930, with moulded cornice and fascia added across façade to form continuous shopfront with the adjoining buildings.  Pitched artificial slate with raised cement coping on left and slightly sprocketted change made to roof.  Painted rendered walls with render quoins, tile and plastic lettering over ground flooring.  Replacement windows to upper floors and enlarged openings with fixed window to ground floor.

Section of rubble stone castellated retaining wall, built c. 1830, possibly incorporating fabric of earlier building.  Various red brick arched openings, partially blocked up, c. 1900.  Concrete facing to arches of surviving openings.

Freestanding barn-style gable-fronted former Roman Catholic church, founded c. 1735, rebuilt c. 1790 and in use until 1842.  Now in use as community hall.  Extension to rear, c. 1900.  Repointed and refurbished, c. 1980.  Pitched artificial slate roof.  Ribbon pointed rubble stone walls with chamfered corner to shoulder level.  Two cut stone plaques inserted to left of door.  Round-headed opening to first floor with bipartite window.  Square-headed opening to ground floor with cut stone lintel, supported by consoles.  Segmental-arched opening to side entrance, having cut stone Gibbsian surround with double keystone and inserted glazed entrance.

Gable-fronted Gothic Revival former convent chapel, built c. 1895, now in use as hotel entrance lobby and bar.  Hotel complex built 1996.  Pitched slate roof with cut stone finials.  Rendered walls.  Lancet openings with stained glass windows by Meyer of Munich.  Large chancel window taken from earlier church on site, c. 1865.  Retaining some interior features including polished stone columns with moulded stone capitals and bases, hammer beam roof and organ gallery.

Formerly a five-bay two-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1775, now divided and in use as restaurant and public house.  Facade remodelled and two-storey extensions added along laneway to right in late nineteenth century.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack and four pots arranged on square.  Flat roofed dormer windows c. 1935.  Rendered walls with parallel quoins.  Roughcast rendered walls to gable.  Wrought-iron balcony set over heavy cornice, which has egg and dart above.  Dentils over frieze supported by three keystones with consoles overlaid.  Moulded architrave to timber sliding sash windows having exposed boxes to first floor.  Round-headed openings to ground floor.  Retaining interior features.

Formerly a five-bay two-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1775, now divided.  Facade remodelled in late nineteenth century and early twentieth century shopfront added to ground floor.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystack, dormer windows, and having three possibly diagonally placed stone pots dating to seventeenth century.  Rendered walls with quoins to corner, chamfered to head level.  Roughcast rendered walls to gable.  Deep cut stone eaves course to rear.  Mid nineteenth century casement windows to dormers.  Timber sliding sash windows set in moulded render architraves to first floor.  Shopfront comprising glass fascia with gilded channelled lettering, wide panelled pilasters with moulded capitals, fixed windows and recessed engraved glass door.

End-of-terrace seven-bay three-storey house, built c. 1775, in use as part of hotel complex since the end of the nineteenth century.  Hipped slate roof with deep bracketed eaves over five-bays.  Rendered walls with elaborate render details including decorated frieze and elaborate string courses.  Timber sliding sash windows set within elaborate architraves having keystones.  Segmental-arched ground floor window openings and round-headed openings to entrance doors with moulded architraves.  Thought to be built on site of a gaol.  Dungeons uncovered on site c. 1960.

NAME: Pro-Cathedral of Saints Peter and Paul
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan Roman Catholic diocesan pro-cathedral, designed by Dominic Madden and built 1831-42, with spire and porches added in 1871 to designs by J.J. McCarthy.  Became cathedral in 1890. Pitched slate roof to nave.  Three-stage diagonally buttressed tower surmounted by broach spire.  Coursed limestone cut-stone walls with crenellations.  Shields over original openings masked by porch additions of 1871.  Lancet openings with perpendicular tracery.  Timber fluted columns set diagonally and supporting lancet arches to interior.  Carved stone reredos designed by J.J. McCarthy and executed by Handmann and Co.  Painted ceiling by Early & Powell.  Set on site donated by Francis Gore.

Detached two-storey presbytery with breakfront, built c. 1880, with four-bay single-storey L-plan extension to rear.  Pitched artificial slate roof with moulded brick brackets under eaves and red brick chimneystacks having yellow brick string courses.  Red brick walls with yellow brick banding, string course between ground and first floors, quoins and diamond pattern between windows.  Polychrome brick to arched openings having replacement aluminium windows.  Blind lancet arch with paired timber sliding sash windows inset to breakfront.  Set to the rear of the pro-cathedral.

Six-bay two-storey former dance hall, built 1950, converted to furniture showrooms and shopfronts inserted c. 1990.  Comprising large single-bay block with lower five-bay block to the left.  Interior galleried dance hall intact example of 1950 Ballroom of Romance.  Part of nineteenth century gaol walls incorporated into fabric of ballroom.  Pitched corrugated-asbestos roof.  Belfast truss roof with corrugated-sheet over hall on right.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Timber windows set in tripartite and quadripartite openings to lower block and set in sexpartite opening to higher block.  Tall ground floor openings framed with timber shopfront additions.   Stage, sprung floor and galleried dancehall to interior.  Terrazzo floor to entrance and stairs.  Elaborate chimneypiece in former supper rooms.  Built on site of nineteenth century gaol.
Convent graveyard, with interments from c. 1865.  Surrounded by limestone piers and cast-iron railings set on plinth.
Terraced three-bay two-storey commercial premises, built c. 1900, now part of hotel bar.

NAME: Old Ground Hotel
COMPOSITION: Five-bay two-storey former town hall, built c. 1850, now in use as hotel banqueting hall.

NAME: Old Ground Hotel
COMPOSITION: Former town gaol, built c. 1700, probably incorporating fabric of earlier building, now with vaulted ceiling and forming part of hotel complex.
Chamfered-edged gate piers with cast-iron railings on cut-stone chamfered-edged plinth, erected c. 1875.  Set in front of house.

NAME: Knockanaura Castle
COMPOSITION: Remains of former castle, date uncertain.

Detached multiple-bay six-storey former corn mill, built c. 1830, with return to River Fergus at rear.  Gable facade blocked up and ground floor remodelled to accommodate retail outlet, c. 1980.  Pitched natural slate roof.  Coursed rubble limestone walls with pie crust red brick cornice, some rendered sections and some slate hanging.  Cast-iron tie plates at regular intervals on return.  Segmental-arched window openings with red brick dressings and timber framed fixed windows.  Set at slight angle to street, occupying area space between Cornmarket Street and River Fergus.  Aluminium shop windows and door, c. 1980, to retail outlet.

NAME: Waterville
COMPOSITION: Detached three-storey house, built c. 1820.  Hipped slate roof with pair of centrally placed red brick chimneystacks.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Timber panelled door with radial fanlight above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Rear of house faces the street, entrance façade addresses the garden.  Cut-stone gate piers with timber gates to site.

Rubble stone bridge causeway, built c. 1830, across River Fergus.  Comprising three semi-circular arches with cut-stone voussoirs, feeding water to mill race.  Smaller semi-circular arch, now closed up, serving former mill building.  Site of Ennis Mills sold by Earl of Thomond in 1712.  Purchased by Bannatynes in 1824.

Rubble stone causeway, built c. 1830, across River Fergus.  Comprising segmental-arched and smaller semi-circular arched openings with cut-stone voussoirs, which were part of a water management system of former mill buildings.  Site of Ennis Mills sold by Earl of Thomond in 1712.  Purchased by Bannatynes in 1824.

Cut stone mill race, built c. 1830, and waterwheel, forming surviving parts of Ennis Corn Mill, demolished, c. 1980.  Fragment of rendered wall with cut-stone stone semi-circular opening housing axle of mill wheel.  Cast-iron wheel with replacement timber paddles.  Cast-iron sluice gate directly upstream.  Cut-stone faced mill pond leading to millrace.  Rubble stone walls and foot bridge to site, built c. 1990.  Site of Ennis Mills sold by Earl of Thomond in 1712.  Purchased by Bannatynes in 1824.
Cut stone weir with salmon pass and double sluice gates, built 1857.

Single-arch cut stone bridge, built 1857, and widened in 1992 with single span reinforced concrete section refaced with original stonework.  Segmental-arched opening with rusticated voussoirs and flanked by piers with rusticated quoins.  Cut-stone parapet with pointed cut-stone coping.  Narrow round-headed opening in south.

Statue of Maid of Erin, erected 1881, comprising robed female figure, set on drum surmounting Doric column with plinth.  Intertwined shamrocks around drum.  Erected in memory of the Manchester Martyrs.  Similar in design to O’Connell Monument in O’Connell Square.  Relocated to present site in 1966.  Set on red and grey paved roundabout at junction of four roads.

NAME: Westbourne House
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan five-bay two-storey house, built 1856, with entrance portico flanked by gabled breakfronts and having full-height bay windows to right end bay.  Now in use as bishop’s residence.  Pitched natural slate roof with bracketed eaves and cut-limestone stacks.  Rendered walls with render plat bands.  Limestone portico comprising columns and pilasters with entablature above.  Paired of round-headed windows over portico.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Set in wooded grounds.  Elaborate cast-iron gate and rubble stone boundary wall to site.  Built by Alexander Bannatyne, owner of former corn mills.

NAME: Westbourne House
COMPOSITION: Ornate cast-iron gates and cut-limestone piers, built c. 1860, set in coursed limestone rubble walls with squared coping stones.  Forming boundary of Westbourne House along Cusack Road.
Park amenity scheme in three sections incorporating millrace, water wheel and island, opened 1996.  West side under construction in 1997.  Rubble masonry walls with ribbon pointing.

Roadside wall of former military barracks, built c. 1880, flanked by bastions and incorporating flight of stone steps.  Coursed limestone walls with rounded coping stones.  Snecked limestone walls with pistol loops to bastions.  Rubble stone wall encloses site of former barracks to north.

Four-bay two-storey building, built c. 1845, as an extension to former fever hospital, built c. 1825.  In use as auxiliary workhouse in 1855.  In use as militia barracks from 1895 to 1911.  Now forming part of a pair of houses.  Hipped slate roof with rendered gable chimneystack.  Rendered walls.  Replacement timber sliding sash and casement windows.  Timber pedimented porch with timber glazed door.

NAME: Saint Flannan's College
COMPOSITION: Detached U-plan seventeen-bay three-storey Gothic Revival school, built c. 1880, with five-stage breakfront entrance tower and gabled projecting end bays.  Pitched slate roofs with horizontal bands of green slate, red brick chimneystacks, pyramidal tower roof, stone eaves brackets, cut stone copings and finials.  Coursed cut limestone walls with string courses.  Projecting cut-limestone porch with crenellations, corner buttresses, and pointed arch door opening having hood mouldings, inset plaque above and timber panelled double leaf doors.  Cut-stone block-and-start surrounds to pointed arch window openings.  Hood mouldings over some breakfront windows.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.  Fine entrance gates to site.  Various extension including four-bay two-storey block, 1952, staff dining room, 1962, fifteen-bay two-storey block, 1968, and six-bay two-storey block, 1980.

NAME: Corpus Christi Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted single-bay double-height Gothic Revival Roman Catholic church, built c. 1865, with single-bay four-stage tower and spire to left, single-bay single-storey chapel and sacristy to left and eight-bay side elevations.  Six-bay single-storey flat-roofed side aisle added, c. 1900.  Remodelled and polygonal former apse altered, c. 1940, to accommodate use as entrance porch.  Pitched slate roofs with vents to main ridge, cut-stone copings and corbels and cast-iron downpipes.  Pyramidal copper sheeting to spire.  Snecked stone walls with cut-stone dressings and buttresses to side aisle.  Pointed arch openings with leaded coloured and stained glass windows, having cut-stone Y-tracery to aisle.  Pointed arch opening to tower with timber matchboard door, coloured glass fanlight and having carved hood moulding above.  Cut-stone doorcase to remodelled entrance.  Retaining interior features including exposed roof beams, stone corbels, cast-iron spiral staircase to porch, fluted chancel arch, marble altar and altar railings with brass gates.  Cut-stone gate piers with chamfered corners and cast-iron gates to site.  Parochial house to site.

NAME: McInerney's
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1850, with round-headed door opening to centre.  Renovated, c. 1900, with shopfront inserted to right hand side ground floor and façade enrichments added including hood mouldings over openings.  Now disused.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Ruled-and-lined rendered walls to first floor and channelled rendered walls to ground floor with render quoins and string course between floors.  Render pilasters and continuous hood mouldings to ground floor.  Render letters added over shopfront entrance door.  Render hood mouldings with decorative stops to first floor round-headed openings.  Round- and segmental-arched openings with timber doors and fanlights.  Segmental-arched window opening to shopfront, now boarded.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.

NAME: The Spa
COMPOSITION: Group of detached spa buildings.  Detached five-bay single-storey pump house, built c. 1890, with three-bay recessed central block having gablet and single-bay gabled end bays.  Hipped and pitched slate roof with timber finials, decorative timber bargeboards and clay ridge tiles.  Rendered walls with render quoins and crests to gables.  Round-headed openings having hood mouldings.  Timber windows and timber matchboard doors.  Retaining interior features.  Detached three-bay two-storey bath house, built c. 1940.  Flat roof with open lattice concrete balusters to parapet.  Rendered walls with full-height pilasters and entablature.  Timber windows and glazed doors.  Three-bay single- and two-storey ancillary buildings, built c. 1975.  Turnstile at entrance to north.  Bridges span converging streams.  Sulphur well discovered at site c. 1700.

NAME: The Royal Spa Hotel
COMPOSITION: Terraced eight-bay two-storey hotel, built c. 1860, with former integral carriage arch, three-bay single-storey return and originally having polygonal bowed section to rear.  Renovated and extended to rear, c. 1995, with four-bay two-storey return.  Hipped slate and artificial slate roofs with replacement rainwater goods.  Exposed rubble stone walls to front elevation, rendered walls to rear.  Cut-stone voussoirs to former carriage arch opening.  Replacement uPVC windows and timber replacement doors.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Spectacle Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch coursed stone road bridge over river Aille which flows here in a deep gorge, built c. 1850, with cylindrical void over arch.  Designed by Michael O’Loghlin.  Cut-stone voussoirs, splayed piers and cut-stone copings to parapet.

NAME: Teach Ceoil Saint Andrews
COMPOSITION: Freestanding three-bay double-height Gothic Revival Church of Ireland church, dated 1830, with central octagonal-plan two-stage entrance tower.  Converted to use as hall, 1989.  Pitched slate roof with ashar gable copings and pinnacles.  Cut-stone crenellations and pinnacles to tower.  Snecked stone walls with cut-stone quoins.  Corner buttresses, date stone and string course to tower.  Clock added to tower, c. 1900.  Pointed arch openings with cut-stone dressings and hood mouldings.  Timber sliding sash windows with Y-tracery.  Replacement timber panelled double leaf doors with glazed fanlight above.  Three-centred arch opening to rear having timber matchboard door.  Retaining interior features including brass and marble memorial plaques, timber carved pulpit and tiered benches.  Cut-stone gate piers with cast-iron gates set in coursed rubble stone walls.

NAME: C. O'Loughlin
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1870, as a pair with the adjoining house.  Timber shopfront inserted to ground floor, c. 1920.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks, cast-iron rainwater goods and inserted rooflights.  Painted lined-and-ruled rendered walls with inset marble plaque.  Timber shopfront comprising pilasters flanking openings with fascia and cornice above.  Replacement windows with stone sills.  Timber panelled double leaf doors with overlight.  Retaining interior features.  Marble inscribed plaque refers to Thomas O'Loghlan Carron I.R.B.

NAME: Market House Antiques
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay double-height former butter market, built c. 1860, partly refenestrated to accommodate commercial use, c. 1985.  Pitched slate roof with corrugated-iron sheeting to gablets.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Round-headed window and door openings with timber doors, timber sliding sash windows and replacement uPVC windows.  Oculi to gables.  Timber louvres to gablets.

NAME: Clair O'Brien
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1900, with retail outlet to ground floor and two-bay three-storey return.  Two-bay single-storey flat-roofed extension added to return c. 1970.  No longer in commercial use.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Flat roofs to return and extension.  Red brick walls with yellow brick banding and double-height pilasters.  Plastic sign over former retail outlet.  Rendered walls to gable.  Segmental-arched window openings to upper floors with timber sliding sash windows.  Square-headed openings to gable and return with timber sliding sash windows.  Fixed timber window and recessed glazed door to shopfront.  Two-storey outbuilding to rear, now derelict.

NAME: G. Conway
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1860.  Shopfront inserted to ground floor, c. 1940.  Renovated, c. 1985, and, 2000.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystack, metal rooflight and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Roof renewed in 2000.  Painted lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Various projecting plastic shop signs to first floor.  Shopfront comprising panelled pilasters flanking fixed window and timber door with overlight, having fascia, lettering and cornice above.  Replacement windows to upper floors.

NAME: North Clare Tourist Information
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace single-bay two-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1790.  Shopfront inserted to ground floor, c. 1900.  Formerly in use as tourist office, now disused to ground floor.  Pitched Moher flagged roof with rendered chimneystack and concrete coping to gable.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Timber shopfront comprising chamfered pilasters flanking openings with entablature and lettering above.  Two-pane fixed window and timber panelled door to ground floor.  Replacement window to first floor.  Stone flagged floor and timber sheeted counter to interior.

NAME: J. M. Tobin
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay two-storey house, built c. 1830.  Timber shopfront inserted to ground floor c. 1880.  Now disused to ground floor.  Pitched Moher flagged roof with rendered chimneystack.  Ruled-and-lined rendered walls.  Timber pilasters flanking openings with fascia, lettering and cornice above.  Timber shuttering to ground floor window opening.  Timber panelled door.  Moulded render architrave and timber sliding sash windows to first floor.

NAME: Blake and Linnane
COMPOSITION: Pair of semi-detached two-bay two-storey houses, built c. 1830.  Shopfronts inserted c. 1890.  Three-bay single-storey return added to left hand side house, c. 1910.  Five-bay two-storey return added to right hand side house, c. 1920.  Houses no longer in commercial use to ground floor.  Pitched Moher flagged roofs with rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Pitched corrugated-iron roof to extension of right hand side house.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Painted rubble stone walls to extensions.  Corrugated-iron cladding to upper floor extension of right hand side house.  Timber pilaster and entablature shopfronts to ground floor having window shutters, lettering to fascias and moulded cornices.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Flagged area to front with curved walls and three cut-stone steps leading down from street level.

NAME: Ennistymon Bridge
COMPOSITION: Seven-arch rubble stone road bridge over river, built c. 1790, with cut-stone voussoirs, V-cutwaters and bull nose copings.  Inscribed plaque set in road side elevation reads "Michael Conway Volunteer Clare Brigade IRA killed in action 1920. Solas na bhFlaitheas da anam."

NAME: James Griffin
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1850, with timber pubfront inserted to left hand side ground floor.  Pubfront refenestrated, c. 1970.  Refenestrated, c. 1995.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and concrete gable copings.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking openings with lettering to fascia and cornice above.  Mosaic tiling to stall riser.  Replacement uPVC windows with stone sills.  Timber panelled door with overlight, leading to glazed doors.  Outbuildings to rear.

NAME: Armstead
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820, renovated c. 1900 with timber shopfronts inserted to front elevation and to gable.  Two-bay two-storey lean-to return added to rear.  Now disused.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Shopfronts comprising pilasters flanking openings with fascia and moulded cornice above.  Timber panelled doors and boarded opening to street elevation shopfront.  Fixed window to gable shopfront.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber panelled shutters to interior.  Detached two-bay single-storey rubble stone barrel-roofed outbuilding to site.  Rubble stone boundary wall to rear.

NAME: Carrigg's
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1830, with two-bay gable elevation.  Renovated, c. 1900, with two-bay single- and two-storey lean-to added to front and timber pilaster pubfront inserted to gable elevation.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack and single pitched roof to extension.  Rendered walls.  Timber pilaster and entablature shopfront with tripartite fixed window and timber panelled double leaf doors with overlight.  Replacement uPVC windows.

NAME: S. Wall Drapery
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1850, with render shopfront to ground floor having segmental-headed openings.  Renovated, c. 1990, with dormer attic added.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack, cast-iron rainwater goods and rooflight.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with moulded eaves cornice.  Replacement uPVC windows with stone sills to openings.  Timber panelled door with overlight and fixed timber window to ground floor.  Glazed display cabinet doors to shop interior.  Detached three-bay two-storey rubble stone outbuilding with integral carriageway to site.

NAME: Eugene's
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey house, built c. 1870, originally two-storey.  Renovated, c. 1900, and pubfront inserted to ground floor.  Recessed top storey added, c. 1985.  Pitched artificial slate roof, single-pitched roof to slight front projection.  Rendered walls with painted panels flanking first floor timber sliding sash window.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking round-headed bipartite fixed windows and timber matchboard doors, with fascia, lettering and moulded cornice above.  Casement window to second floor.

NAME: Daly's
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey house, built c. 1870.  Renovated c. 1900, with timber shopfront inserted to ground floor.  Dormer attic added, c. 1985.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack, decorative eaves course, cast-iron rainwater goods and rooflight.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with render quoins and architraves to upper floors.  Timber shopfront comprising fluted pilasters flanking fixed window and timber panelled door with toplight, having fascia, lettering, fluted consoles and moulded cornice above.  Timber sliding sash windows to upper floors.

NAME: Stack
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace single-bay three-storey house, built c. 1860.  Extended to rear with two-bay two-storey return and timber pubfront inserted to ground floor.  Renovated and attic accommodation added, c. 1995.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystack and rooflight.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with render quoins and having moulded render architraves to upper floor openings.  Timber shopfront comprising pilasters flanking fixed window and timber panelled door with overlight, having fascia, console, dentillated cornice and retractable canopy above.  Replacement timber windows to upper floors.

NAME: Crosbie
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1870, with three-bay side elevation.  Timber shopfront inserted, c. 1900.  Renovated c. 2005.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Timber shopfront comprising chamfered pilasters flanking tripartite fixed windows and panelled door with overlight, having entablature above.  Replacement timber windows.  Part glazed door to side elevation.
APPRAISAL:
Winner of Best Traditional Shop Front 2005.

Slate roof replaced artificial slate - timber windows replaced upvc.

NAME: Slatt's Bookmakers
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1870, with single-bay canted oriel window to first floor.  Timber shopfront inserted c. 1890.  Now disused to ground floor.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystack and gabled slated dormer windows.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with moulded dentillated eaves course and moulded string course at first floor lintel level having decorated band below.  Shopfront comprising chamfered pilasters with decorative capitals flanking fixed bipartite window and timber panelled door with overlight, having canted fascia above.  Oriel window comprising fluted render pilasters flanking openings with decorative band and pediment above.  Moulded architraves to second floor openings.  Replacement windows.

NAME: Byrne
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1790.  Shopfront inserted c. 1900.  Pitched Moher flagged roof with cast-iron rainwater goods.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Timber shopfront comprising pilasters flanking tripartite fixed window and timber panelled door with fascia, lettering and cornice above.  Metal window guard to fixed window.  Timber sliding sash windows to upper floors.  Retaining interior features.

Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1790.  Ground floor remodelled to accommodate commercial use, c. 1890, with door openings altered and tripartite timber sliding sash window inserted.  Pitch Moher flagged slate roof with rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills to upper floors.  Timber matchboard door with five pane overlight and timber double leaf doors to former shop.

NAME: Ennistymon Courthouse (former)
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay single-storey former courthouse with breakfront end bays, built c. 1800, having recessed bay to right.  Now in use as art gallery.  Hipped artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Dressed rubble stone walls with recessed blind arches to openings, having cut-stone and red brick voussoirs.  Probably originally having central entrance bay, now altered.  Timber matchboard double leaf doors with cobweb fanlight.  Round-headed window openings with timber sliding sash windows.  Square-headed opening with red brick dressings and timber panelled door to recessed entrance.  Wrought-iron railings set on cut-stone plinth.
Section of limestone flagged paving, built c. 1870, with concrete bollard.

NAME: A. Healy
COMPOSITION: Detached two-bay two-storey over basement house with dormer attic, built c. 1860, with segmental-headed carriageway attached to left.  Timber shopfront inserted, c. 1900.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Lined-and-rendered walls.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking fixed bipartite windows, timber panelled door with overlight and timber glazed doors with overlight, having fascia and moulded cornice above.  Tripartite fixed windows to stall risers lighting basement.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Pair of detached two- and three-bay single-storey outbuildings incorporating fabric of earlier house to right.  Cobbled drain and flagged footpath to front.

NAME: O'Leaghrain
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1870, with single-bay canted oriel window to first floor.  Timber pubfront inserted, c. 1900.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Hipped artificial slate roof to oriel window.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with dentilated eaves course.  Timber pilaster and entablature shopfront surround fixed window and timber single and double leaf doors with overlights.  Timber sash windows to upper floors.

NAME: Falls Hotel
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey over basement former house with central pedimented breakfront bay, built c. 1760, now in use as hotel. May incorporate pre18th century fabric. Renovated and extended to rear with thirteen-bay three-storey block having dormer attic.  Extended to side in 1997 with four-bay two-storey block over raised platform.  Pitched slate roof with rendered gable chimneystacks and cut-stone copings.  Exposed rubble stone walls with moulded impost moulding to entrance door and moulded cornicing to pediment.  Replacement timber sliding sash windows.  Round-headed door opening with timber panelled door having plain fanlight and flanking by sidelights.  Lunette with fixed window to pediment.  Retaining significant interior features including panelled window reveals, extensive ceiling plasterwork, centrepieces, cornices, lugged architraves, panelled shutter and staircase.  Flight of cut stone steps leading to entrance.

NAME: Church of the Blessed Virgin Mary and Sain Michael
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic Church, built 1952-54, with stepped central breakfront, single-bay four-stage bell tower to right having attached single-bay single-storey bowed-ended baptistery, eight-bay nave elevations and eight-bay single-storey side aisle to right.  Pitched copper sheeted roof to nave and flat roofs to tower, aisle and baptistery.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Full-height timber windows to glazed entrance bay, with concrete mullion and transoms forming cross.  Timber multiple paned clerestory windows with rendered columns between.  Concrete louvres to tower belfry.  Retaining interior features including built in confessionals to side aisle, marble altars, gallery to rear and stations of the cross.  Wrought-iron gates and rusticated stone piers set in rubble stone wall.

End-of-terrace two-bay three-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1870, with canted bay window to ground floor.  Built as a pair with the adjoining house.  Now vacant.  Pitched slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, rendered chimneystack, red clay pots, uPVC rainwater goods and rooflight.  Rendered walls.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber panelled door with overlight.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: M. Honan Victualler
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1840.  Render façade enrichments and timber shopfront inserted c. 1890.  Now disused to ground floor.  Pitched slate roof with red clay ridge tiles, cast-iron rainwater goods, consoles to eaves course, rendered chimneystacks and yellow clay pots.  Rendered walls with render quoins, moulded architraves to upper floor windows and Marian plaque to first floor.  Shopfront comprising fluted pilasters with fluted consoles flanking openings having fascia and cornice above.  Fixed window with wrought-iron grill and recessed timber glazed double leaf doors approached by tiles and wrought-iron gates.  Replacement uPVC door and overlight to ground floor.  Replacement uPVC windows to upper floors.

NAME: Ó Domnalláin
COMPOSITION: Pair of semi-detached single-bay two-storey houses with gabled half-dormer windows, built c. 1880.  Timber shopfront inserted to house to right, c. 1940.  Pitched Liscannor slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, rendered chimneystacks, red clay pots, rendered copings and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls.  Retaining original timber sliding sash windows to right house and with replacement timber sliding sash windows to left house.  Shopfront comprising fluted pilasters flanking fixed window and timber panelled door with fascia and dentillated cornice above.

NAME: C.L. Looney
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1840, with timber shopfront inserted, c. 1900.  Now disused to ground floor.  Pitched slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, rendered chimneystacks, yellow clay pots and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Timber shopfront comprising pilasters flanking fixed windows, timber panelled door and timber glazed double leaf doors with overlights, having fascia and moulded cornice above.  Retaining original timber sliding sash windows to upper floors.

NAME: John Vaughan Auctioneers
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1860, with timber shopfront inserted, c. 1900.  Pitched artificial sate roof with concrete ridge tiles, cast-iron rainwater goods, timber box eaves and rendered chimneystacks.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking fixed window and timber panelled and timber glazed double leaf doors with overlights, having carved consoles, fascia and cornice above.  Retaining timber sliding sash windows to upper floors.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Bank of Ireland
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey purpose-built bank and manager’s house, built c. 1870.  Ground floor renovated, c. 1990.  Pitched slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, cast-iron rainwater goods, timber box eaves, consoled cornice, rendered chimneystacks and yellow clay pots.  Rendered walls with vermiculated quoins and panels to ground floor, moulded render fascia over ground floor openings and raised quoins to upper floors.  Segmental-arched openings with moulded architraves, concrete sills, timber panelled double leaf doors, replacement uPVC windows and ATM to ground floor.  Retaining original timber sliding sash windows to upper floors.

NAME: Michael A. Nagle and Co. Chartered Accountants
COMPOSITION: Terraced five-bay two-storey former house, built c. 1870, with segmental-arched integral carriage arch.  Now in use as offices.  Pitched artificial slate roof with moulded timber box eaves, rendered chimneystacks, yellow clay pots, render coping and replacement rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with render quoins and moulded segmental-arched panel to first floor.  Round-headed openings to ground floor having moulded architraves, cast-iron decorative sill guards and gold leaf lettering.  Square-headed openings to upper floors.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Round-headed door opening with timber panelled door and plain fanlight.  Timber sheeted gates to carriage arch.

NAME: Ennistymon Medical Centre
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1860, with replacement timber shopfront inserted, c. 1985.  Pitched slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, cast-iron rainwater goods, consoled cornice, rendered chimneystack and rooflight.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with render quoins and moulded render architraves to upper floors.  Retaining original timber sliding sash windows to upper floors.

NAME: The Sugan Chair Restaurant
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1860, with timber shopfront inserted, c. 1930.  Pitched artificial slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, rooflights, cast-iron rainwater goods, rendered chimneystack, red clay pots and consoled cornice.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with render quoins and moulded render architraves to upper floors.  Exposed rubble stone walls to ground floor.  Shopfront comprising carved pilasters, cast-iron columns, tripartite fixed windows and timber panelled and glazed doors with fascia and moulded cornice above.  Retaining original timber sliding sash windows to upper floors.

Terraced single-bay three-storey house, built c. 1860, with shopfront inserted, c. 1980.  Shopfront now disused.  Pitched slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, rendered chimneystacks, consoled cornice and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with render quoins and moulded architraves to upper floors.  Tiled walls to ground floor.  Replacement uPVC windows to upper floors.  Aluminium fixed window and door to ground floor.

NAME: Cooley's House
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey house, built c. 1870, with shopfront inserted c, 1920.  Pitched slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, cast-iron rainwater goods and rendered chimneystacks.  Exposed rubble stone walls.  Timber shopfront comprising pilasters flanking tripartite window and timber panelled double leaf doors with fascia and moulded cornice above.  Retaining original timber sliding sash windows to upper floors.

NAME: James Devitt Hardware
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1840, with façade enrichments added c. 1890, and timber shopfront inserted, c. 1910.  Pitched slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, rooflights, cast-iron rooflights, moulded and consoled cornice and rendered chimneystacks.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with rusticated decoration, double-height pilaster strips with consoles, and roll mouldings openings to upper floors.  Segmental-arched openings to upper floors with timber sliding sash windows.  Timber shopfront comprising panelled pilasters having carved consoles, flanking timber fixed windows with curved panes flanking recessed timber glazed double leaf doors with etched overlight, having fascia and cornice above.  Mosaic threshold with lettering.  Retaining interior features including timber shelving, timber panelled counter and terrazzo flooring.

End-of-terrace three-bay two-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1880, with timber shopfront to ground floor and two-bay two-storey return.  Shopfront no longer in commercial use.  Pitched artificial slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, rendered chimneystacks, gabled dormers and uPVC rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with render façade enrichments such as vermiculated quoins, architraves to first floor and eaves course.  Timber shopfront comprising panelled pilasters, carved consoles, fascia and moulded cornice.  Timber fixed windows with curved panes leading to timber glazed double leaf doors.  Timber panelled door with overlight.  Tiled plinth to shopfront and polychrome tiled thresholds to doors.  Segmental-arched openings with timber sliding sash windows to first floor.

NAME: Nursing Home
COMPOSITION: Gateway to former Ennistymon Union Workhouse complex, built 1842, now in use as gateway to nursing home.  Comprising three tooled limestone cut-stone piers with sandstone cappings, having square-headed pedestrian gate to left and set in coursed Liscannor stone boundary walls.  Workhouse demolished, c. 1925.

NAME: Kilfinaghty Public Library
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Church of Ireland church, dated 1810, comprising four-bay nave and a later three-stage entrance tower. Design of tower by the Pain brothers. Derelict at time of survey but restored (2001) for use as public library.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone gable copings.  Ashar pinnacles and crenellations to tower.  Rubble stone walls with cut-stone eaves course, quoins and plinth.  String courses to tower.  Round-headed openings with cut-stone reveals, voussoirs, keystones and sills, now blocked.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers and mausolea.  Cut-stone gateway with elliptical-headed opening having inscribed plaque, approached by flight of steps.

NAME: Corrofin Union Workhouse
COMPOSITION: Detached fifteen-bay single-storey building, built c. 1845, originally part of Corrofin Union Workhouse.  Now partly in use as OPW National Monuments subdepot.  Pitched slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, limestone eaves course, cast-iron rainwater goods, cut-stone gable copings, rendered chimneystacks and red clay pots.  Hipped roof to return.  Roughcast rendered walls over rubble stone construction and having cut-stone plinth.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.  Segmental-arched door openings with cut-limestone architraves, timber matchboard doors and approached by limestone steps.  Some openings now blocked or altered.  Other buildings in complex now demolished.

NAME: P. Frawley
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace six-bay two-storey house, built c. 1870, timber pubfront inserted c. 1900.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with cut-stone eaves course.  Timber fluted pilaster pubfront with decorative capitals, entablature and raised lettering.  Fixed window with incised sill and timber panelled door to pubfront.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.  Timber panelled door with overlight and sidelights.  Retaining interior features including timber shelving, sheeted bar counter and sheeted timber screen with decorative pediment.

End-of-terrace five-bay single-storey house, built c. 1860, timber shopfront inserted c. 1900.  Shopfront now disused.  Pitched Moher pitched roof with rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Timber shopfront comprising pilasters, name fascia and moulded cornice.  Display windows now boarded.  Timber matchboard half glazed door to shopfront.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.  Timber matchboard door with overlight leading to residential accommodation.

NAME: Claremont Hotel
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited ten-bay three-storey hotel, built c. 1850, originally two-storey.  Top floor added and two-bay three-storey return added, c. 1985.  Hipped artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with vermiculated quoins, moulded cornice to first floor, vermiculated moulded architraves to openings and render plaques with affixed signage.  Replacement aluminium windows.  Stone sills to ground and first floors.  Concrete canopy over entrance.  Entablature and pilasters to pub entrance on return.

NAME: The Old Rectory
COMPOSITION: Detached T-plan four-bay two-storey former rectory, built c. 1905, now in use as private house.  Comprising projecting single-storey entrance bay and central gablet, flanked by projecting hipped single-bay two-storey block and recessed two-bay two-storey block.  Single-bay single-storey canted bay window to left side elevation.  Single-bay two-storey return to rear.  Two-bay two-storey flat-roofed lower block and single-bay two-storey lower return having single-bay single-storey lean-to, added c. 1990.  Pitched slate roof with red brick chimneystacks, clay ridge crestings, clay finials and decorative timber bargeboards.  Red brick English garden wall bond walls.  Segmental-arched openings with replacement uPVC windows.  Timber panelled half glazed door with overlight.  Detached four-bay single-storey outbuilding to rear.  Rubble stone gate piers.

NAME: Market House
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited detached three-bay two-storey market house with gabled central bay, built c. 1740.  Half hipped slate roof.  Exposed rubble stone walls.  Round-headed openings to ground floor, formerly forming arcade, remodelled, c. 1920.  Recessed timber matchboard double leaf door to central arch.  Timber sliding sash windows to window openings, set in blocked former arches to ground floor.  Former openings to side elevation now blocked.  Attached single-bay single-storey segmental-headed carriage arch to left having cut-stone voussoirs.  Rubble stone boundary wall to rear yard.

NAME: Methodist Church (former)
COMPOSITION: Attached single-cell three-bay single-storey former Methodist church, built c. 1810, renovated in 1886, and used as Church of Ireland school from 1914-32.  Now in use as residence.  Pitched artificial slate roof.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls.  Lancet openings with stone sills, cast-iron diamond paned glazed upper sections and timber horizontally glazed lower sections.  Pointed arch door opening with timber matchboard doors having decorative strap hinges.  Spearheaded wrought-iron railings and gate.

NAME: Saint Caimin's Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Church of Ireland church, built 1789, comprising four-bay nave with single-bay three-stage crenellated tower added to left hand side, 1831, and single-bay single-storey lean-to vestry to rear.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone copings and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Crenellated cut-stone parapet and corner pinnacles to tower.  Single-pitched roof to vestry.  Rubble stone walls with cut-stone quoins.  Lancet windows with cut-stone surrounds and replacement aluminium windows.  Triple lancet leaded glass windows to chancel.  Pointed arch door opening with timber matchboard door.  Graveyard to site with various cut stone grave markers and mausolea.  Wrought-iron piers with wrought-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Keane's Bar
COMPOSITION: Terraced four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1890, with pubfront inserted to ground floor.  Pitched slate roof with lined-and-ruled rendered chimneystacks, aluminium rainwater goods and with flat-roofed felt canopy over pubfront.  Channelled rendered walls to ground floor, lined-and-ruled rendered walls with honeycombed rendered panels to first floor, having render end pilasters, moulded render architraves and plat band between floors.  Plastic lettering set on timber fascia over pubfront.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Replacement timber glazed doors and display window.

NAME: Old School House
COMPOSITION: Detached U-plan five-bay single-storey former school with dormer attic, dated 1846, comprising recessed three-bay central block with projected gabled end bays.  Now in use as house.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks, cut-stone gable copings and dormer windows.  Rubble stone walls with cut-stone string courses and plaques to gabled bays.  Ogee-headed central door opening with carved hood moulding, timber panelled double leaf doors and decorative fanlight.  Square-headed window openings with carved label mouldings and replacement timber windows.  Keystones with inscribed plaques above to former door openings.  Rubble stone boundary walls, cut-stone piers and wrought-iron gate to site.

NAME: Saint Joseph's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1839, comprising three-bay side elevations and single-bay transepts with three-stage entrance tower added in 1861, and broach spire added in 1863.  Porches added to transepts.  Pitched artificial slate roof.  Pinnacles and cut-stone spire with lucarnes to tower.  Concrete eaves banding, c. 1985.  Rubble stone walls with cut-stone quoins and inset plaque.  Diagonal buttresses, cut-stone string course and dentillated cornice to tower.  Four-centred arch door opening.  Lancet windows with cut-stone architraves and replacement timber window.  Leaded stained glass windows to porch.  Retaining interior features including cast-iron spiral staircase, gallery to rear, clustered columns, Tuscan timber columns to galleried transepts, tiled central aisle and coffered ceiling.  Pair of freestanding cut-stone stoups and cut-stone piers with moulded pyramidal capping to site.

NAME: M. Lynch
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1890, with render façade enrichments.  Ground floor remodelled to accommodate commercial use, c. 1970, now disused to ground floor.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack having stone and clay pots.  Lined-and-ruled rendered vermiculated block effect walls with decorative render quoins and eaves band.  Decorative render banding surrounding ground floor openings, with decorative render name fascia and letter above.  Replacement timber casement windows to first floor.  Fixed timber windows and timber glazed and matchboard doors to ground floor.

NAME: D. Mác Cruitin
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1890, shopfront inserted, c. 1930.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods.  Pebbledashed walls to first floor with render plat bands and moulded architraves.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking openings with tiled stall riser, having moulded consoles, fascia, lettering and moulded cornice above.  Chamfered detail and timber sill guards to fixed display window.

NAME: Station House
COMPOSITION: Detached former railway station complex, built 1857, comprising L-plan three-bay two-storey station master’s house with two-bay two-storey return, and four-bay single-storey station to right, having six-bay single-storey flat roof canopy over former platform.  Now in use as guest house.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls.  Cast-iron columns to former platform.  Timber sliding sash windows to former station.  Replacement uPVC windows to house.  Roughcast rendered chamfered gate piers with wrought-iron gate to site.  Former goods shed to site.  Foundation stone of West Clare Railway laid by Charles Stewart Parnell to rear of this site.

Graveyard of former Church of Ireland church, with interments from 1802.  Pair of freestanding single-bay single-storey gable-fronted limestone cut-stone mausolea having cross finials.  Various cut-stone grave markers.  Lined-and-ruled rendered screen walls and piers to site.  Church demolished, c. 1985.

NAME: Tulla Branch Library
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey former market house, date 1843, now in use as library.  Single-bay single-storey recessed extension to right, c. 1990.  Hipped artificial slate roof with central gablet, cut-stone eaves course and clay ridge crestings.  Cut-limestone walls, channelled to ground floor, with quoins, voussoirs, impost mouldings and having inset plaque and crest to gablet.
