Elliptical-headed openings with fixed timber windows and timber sheeted double leaf doors.  Plaque inscribed ‘This house was built by Thos Browne, Esq. Newgrove. A.D. 1843.’

NAME: Market House
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey building, built c. 1840, possibly originally a market house.  In use as R.I.C. barracks in 1919.  Now in use as house.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Rendered walls with render quoins and raised surrounds to first floor openings.  Cut-stone voussoirs, keystones, piers, imposts and mouldings to ground floor openings.  Windows and doors now inserted to altered ground floor openings.  Replacement uPVC windows to first floor openings.  Steps leading to entrance doors.

NAME: Tulla House
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan three-bay single-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1860, having single-bay two-storey return to rear.  Possibly originally a presbytery.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks, deep eaves having paired timber consoles and gabled dormer windows having timber bargeboards.  Rendered walls with render quoins.  Elliptical-headed door opening to centre having sidelights and fanlights, surrounded by timber panelled pilaster doorcase.  Tripartite timber sliding sash windows to ground floor and timber sliding sash windows to gabled dormers.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-stone piers with moulded pyramidal capping.

NAME: Convent of Mercy
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey convent, built 1883, with canted bay window to ground floor left hand side.  Pitched slate roof with red brick chimneystacks, paired timber eaves consoles and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with plaque above.  Segmental-arched door opening with timber pilaster doorcase, timber matchboard door, sidelights and fanlight.  Segmental-arched openings with timber sliding sash windows.  Moulded architraves and stained glass to bay window openings.

Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1890, with timber shopfront to ground floor.  Single-bay two-storey return added to rear, c. 1985.  No longer in commercial use to ground floor.  Pitched slate roof with concrete gable copings, rendered chimneystacks and having flat roof to extension.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with vermiculated sections, render pilasters, string course between floors and moulded architraves having vermiculated keystones.  Render lettering between door openings.  Shopfront comprising pilasters with consoles, fascia and cornice above.  Timber panelled doors with overlights.  Timber casement window to former shopfront.  Timber sliding sash windows.

NAME: Tulla Courthouse
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey courthouse, dated 1838, with three-bay double-height central block, flanked by breakfront entrance end bays.  Three-bay side elevations and two-bay single-storey lean-to return.  Now also in use as County Council offices.  Hipped slate roof with pedimented projecting clock, cut-stone chimneystacks and cut-stone eaves course.  Single-pitched slate roof to return.  Cut-limestone walls and quoins with string course under windows and blank plaques over entrance doors.  Squared rubble stone walls to sides and rear.  Limestone pedimented door surrounds with timber panelled double leaf doors and overlights.  Round-headed window openings with raised surrounds.  Replacement uPVC windows.

NAME: Chruch of Ireland Graveyard
COMPOSITION: Graveyard to former Church of Ireland church, with various cut-stone grave markers and mausolea, from c. 1800-1995.  Cast-iron gates and canted cut-stone piers set in rubble stone boundary walls.  Church now demolished.

NAME: E. Richardson
COMPOSITION: Terraced seven-bay two-storey house, built c. 1850, with square-headed integral carriage arch to left hand side.  Timber shopfront inserted, c. 1900.  Pitched slate roof with brick and concrete block chimneystacks and cast-iron downpipe.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with rusticated render quoins and raised render surrounds to openings.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking replacement display window and timber matchboard double leaf doors with overlight, having fascia, marbleised lettering and moulded cornice above.  Timber matchboard doors and timber sliding sash windows to openings.

NAME: John Crotty Italian Warehouse
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace five-bay two-storey split-level house, built c. 1850, with carriage arch and five-bay side elevation.  Shopfronts, c. 1900, inserted to ground floor.  Pitched slate and artificial slate roofs with brick chimneystack having decorative pots, aluminium gutters and cast-iron downpipe.  Rendered walls with render quoins.  Three shopfronts comprising pilasters flanking openings with carved consoles, fascia, marbleised lettering and moulded cornices above.  Fixed round-headed perpendicular windows and timber panelled door to shopfronts.  Timber sliding sash windows to upper floors, with moulded render surrounds to right hand side openings and keystones to left hand side openings.

NAME: Saint Flannan's Church of Ireland Cathedral
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan double-height Church of Ireland cathedral, built c. 1200 comprising gable-fronted nave with four-bay side elevations, single-bay transepts, single-bay chancel and square-plan single-bay three-stage crenellated tower to crossing.  Renovated, c. 1780, with additional stage added to tower.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone gable copings.  Rubble stone walls with relieving arch over entrance and buttresses having cut-stone skews and pyramidal copings.  String course to tower.  Lancet windows with cast-iron quarries and cut-stone dressings.  Tripartite lancet opening with colonnette mullions and stained glass to chancel.  Pointed arch opening with moulded cut-stone surround and timber matchboard double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features including rib vaulting under tower, full-height oak screen and exposed timber roof.  Bells installed in 1892.  Cut-stone piers, c. 1780, with moulded capping having acorn-cup finials to site.

NAME: Killaloe Bridge
COMPOSITION: Thirteen-arch road bridge over Rive Shannonr, built c. 1760, with segmental-arched openings and refuges along road side.  Rubble stone walls with cut-stone voussoirs, V-cutwaters and cut-stone bull nose copings.  Arch remodelled, memorial inserted and metal railings added, c. 1960.  Memorial commemorates deaths of  M. O'Neigill, Michael MacMathghamna, Martan MacGiollaidhe, Alphonsus MacRuaidhri, Michael Mac Aadhagain in 1920.  Bridge straddles two counties.

NAME: Saint Flannan's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1837, comprising three-bay gabled entrance front, four-bay side elevations and single-bay transepts.  Pitched slate roof with cast-iron downpipe, dentilated eaves course and metal cross finials.  Coursed cut-stone to entrance front and rubble stone to remaining walls.  Lancet openings with cut-stone voussoirs, stained glass windows and Harry Clarke windows.  Four-centred arch door openings with timber matchboard doors.  Retaining interior features including render panels behind altar, timber cross rib vaulted ceiling, winged dove at crossing, carved marble altar and tabernacle, choir gallery with sheeted balustrade and chamfered timber columns.  Freestanding single-bay single-storey gable-fronted rubble stone-built early-Christian oratory moved to site following flooding of original site by the Ardnacrusha scheme.

NAME: Abbey House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1800, with single-bay single-storey recessed end bay to the right and pair of three-bay two-storey returns.  Glazed porch added to front and two-bay two-storey extension added to rear.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Flat roof to extension to rear and to entrance porch.  Roughcast rendered walls, with rendered walls to returns and extension.  Tripartite timber sliding sash windows with stone sills to front elevation.  Timber sliding sash windows to sides and rear.  Timber half glazed door to glazed porch.  Retaining interior timber panelled shutters.  Rubble stone boundary walls to adjoining courtyard with cut-stone gate piers and timber gates.  Detached two-bay two-storey rubble stone outbuilding to site.

NAME: Killaloe Courthouse
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey court house, built c. 1830, with three-bay double-height central block, flanked by breakfront entrance end bays.  Hipped artificial slate roof with chimneystacks and cut-stone eaves course.  Cut-sandstone walls with quoins, string course under windows and blank plaques over entrance doors.  Squared rubble stone to sides and rear.  Raised limestone pedimented door surrounds with timber matchboard double leaf doors and overlights.  Round-headed window openings with raised surrounds and timber sliding sash windows.  Stone steps leading to doors.  Rubble stone boundary wall to yard to rear.

NAME: The Riverside Inn
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited detached three-bay single-storey house with half-dormer attic, built c. 1770, with single-bay side elevation and two-bay single-storey return with half-dormer attic.  Two-bay single-storey return added and shopfronts inserted, c. 1920.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and gabled dormers.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with render quoins, render architraves and inset date plaque to gable wall.  Shopfronts comprising pilasters flanking openings with fascia and moulded cornice above.  Stone plaque reading ‘Frederick Square 1733.’

NAME: Little Church of Cratloe
COMPOSITION: Detached gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1858, with gabled projecting entrance porch, four-bay side elevations and two-bay single-storey lean-to sacristy to rear.  Pitched artificial slate roof with courses of red slate, cut-stone gable copings, cut-stone bellcote and cross finial.   Single-pitched roof to sacristy with cut-stone chimneystack.  Squared rubble stone walls with inset inscribed date stone and quoins.  Cut-stone gable wall and glazed side walls to porch, c. 1986.  Lancet openings with cut-stone architraves.  Leaded coloured glass to sacristy windows.  Pointed arch opening with timber matchboard door to sacristy.  Retaining interior features including exposed roof timbers, reredos, sculpted altar, doors to sacristy, sheeted timber wainscoting and marble memorial to Father James O'Shea.  Rubble stone boundary wall with castellated coping to site.

NAME: The Old House Bar
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1775, with gablets over first floor openings, two-bay side elevation and two-bay two-storey return.  Timber pubfronts inserted to ground floor.  Single-bay two-storey return to rear, c. 1980.  Pitched artificial slate roof with brick chimneystacks and timber bargeboards to gablets.  Flat roof to return.  Roughcast rendered walls with buttress to front elevation, timber applied to first floor and inset plaque to gable.  Pubfronts comprising pilasters flanking openings with fascias and dentillated cornices.  Timber fixed windows and timber panelled door to pubfronts.  Replacement windows and doors to openings.  Plaque inscribed ‘Georges Street 1733.’

Corner-sited detached five-bay two-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1840, with two-bay two-storey return and attached single-storey outbuilding to rear.  Pitched green natural slate roof with brick corniced chimneystacks.  Lime-washed rubble stone walls.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Replacement timber glazed door.  Timber panelled shutters to interior.  Jostle stone at corner of house.  Rendered garden wall with rendered piers to front.

NAME: Credit Union
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace three-bay two-storey former house with dormer attic, built c. 1820, with oblique gable and single-bay two-storey return.  Formerly in use as Garda Station, now in use as credit union.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Rooflights inserted to rear pitch.  Rendered walls.  Round-headed door opening with timber pilaster doorcase, fanlight and timber panelled double leaf doors, approached by flight of steps.  Single and tripartite timber sliding sash windows.  Rendered boundary walls to site.

NAME: Saint Mary's and Saint Finaghta's Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1812, comprising gable-fronted entrance with four-bay side elevations and two-bay transepts.  Single-bay single-storey lean-to chancel added to rear, 1979.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone gable copings and bellcote.  Single-pitched roof to extension.  Roughcast rendered walls with inset plaque.  Lancet openings with Y-tracery glazing.  Cut-stone tracery to transept openings.  Timber matchboard doors.  Retaining interior features including exposed roof timbers on stone corbels, timber open balustrade to choir loft and timber panelled reredos.

NAME: Mount Ievers House
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay three-storey over raised basement Georgian house, built 1730-1737, to designs by John Rothery.  Hipped slate roof with cut-stone eaves course, moulded frieze and rendered chimneystack.  Red brick walls to south elevation, cut-limestone to north elevation, having cut-stone quoins, string courses and architraves.  Roughcast rendered walls to sides with cut-stone plinth and string courses.  Segmental-arched openings to basement and square-headed openings to upper floors with timber sliding sash windows having thick glazing bars and limestone sills.  Carved limestone pilaster and entablature doorcases with timber panelled doors to south and north elevations.  Flight of limestone steps leading to south entrance.  Detached eight-bay single-storey outbuilding with round-headed integral carriage arch and moulded architraves to openings.  Red brick piers with ball finials having pedimented round-headed flanking niches and bellcote, set in rubble stone boundary walls.

NAME: Ailled Irish Bank
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey over part-raised basement red brick bank and manager’s house, built c. 1890, with two-bay two-storey advanced bay to left having single-bay full-height canted bay window and square-headed door opening.  Hipped artificial slate roof with brick chimneystacks, cut-stone copings, deep eaves and limestone eaves course.  Red brick walls with cut-stone plinth, string courses and dressings to openings.  Carved scrolled pediment over entrance door.  Timber sliding sash and replacement windows to openings.  Timber panelled door with overlight.  Retaining interior features.  Red brick gate pier and plinths with limestone dressings and wrought-iron railings and gates.  Cut stone steps leading to entrance door.

NAME: Bank of Ireland
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited detached seven-bay two-storey bank and manager’s house, built c. 1880, with advanced end bays.  Single-bay two-storey flat-roofed return to rear.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks, rendered parapet and moulded eaves course.  Rendered walls, channelled to ground floor, with moulded string courses between floors.  Timber panelled door with overlight.  Replacement windows to openings.  Retaining interior features.  Stone steps leading to entrance door.  Rendered plinth walls with cut-stone copings to site.

NAME: Nolan
COMPOSITION: Terraced four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1870, with render and tiled shopfront to ground floor.  Pitched artificial slate roof with clay ridge cresting, rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with continuous label mouldings having decorative stops to first floor openings.  Shopfront comprising fluted pilasters with inset high relief tile panels flanking openings, having figures forming consoles, fascia, lettering and moulded cornice above.  Segmental-arched openings to first floor with timber sliding sash windows.  Replacement fittings to ground floor openings.

NAME: Purthill's Guest House
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1890, with shopfront to right hand side ground floor and two-bay two-storey return.  Canted oriel windows added to upper floor right hand side and full-height canted bay windows to left hand side.  Now also in use as guesthouse.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls.  Timber shopfront comprising chamfered pilasters flanking tripartite fixed window and timber panelled door with overlight, having fascia and moulded cornice above.  Segmental-arched door opening with timber pilaster doorcase, timber panelled door and fanlight.  Timber sliding sash windows.

NAME: Kilkee Railway Station (former)
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay single-storey former railway station, built 1892, with pair of single-bay single-storey flat-roofed projecting porches, full-length canopy over platform and two-bay single-storey flat-roofed lower return to rear.  Two-bay single-storey end bay added, c. 1980.  Now in use as house.  Pitched slate roof with red brick chimneystacks.  Glazed canopy with cast-brackets supported by cast-iron columns and having timber sheeted gable ends.  Rendered walls with painted brick plinth, quoins and block-and-start architraves.  Six-bay timber glazed screen.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.  Timber glazed doors.

NAME: Bernadette House
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1850, shopfront inserted, c. 1920.  Shopfront now disused.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with render quoins and moulded architraves to openings.  Render shopfront, comprising decorative consoles, fascia and moulded cornice over fixed windows and timber panelled door.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber panelled door.

NAME: Saint James's Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height gable-fronted Church of Ireland church, built c.1845, to design attributed to the Pain brothers, with gabled projecting porch, four-bay nave elevations and vestry to rear.  Pitched slate and artificial slate roofs with cut-stone bellcote.  Dressed stone walls with cut-stone buttresses.  Hood mouldings to chancel and entrance gable windows.  Lancet openings with ashar dressings and cast-iron and timber traceried windows.  Pointed arch opening with timber matchboard door.  Rubble stone boundary walls with cast-iron piers and gates, c.1935.  Aedicule to side boundary wall with castellated parapet and urn finial.

NAME: Bayview House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1880, with recessed single-bay single-storey block to left.  Hipped artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks having decorative clay pots and deep eaves with console brackets.  Rendered walls with render plat bands and eaves band.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Segmental-arched door opening with timber pilaster doorcase, timber panelled door and cobweb fanlight.  Boot scrapers to each side of door.  Rendered boundary wall to site.

End-of-terrace three-bay two-storey over basement house, built c. 1850.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Rendered walls with render quoins and moulded render surrounds to window openings.  Round-headed door opening with timber pilaster doorcase, fanlight and timber panelled door, approached by flight of steps.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Cast-iron railings set on rendered plinth to basement area.

NAME: Sykes House
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1845, with four-bay two-storey return.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and render eaves band.  Pitched artificial slate to return.  Rendered walls to ground floor, roughcast rendered walls to first floor, with render quoins, string course between floors and moulded render architraves.  Segmental-arched opening with timber pilastered doorcase, timber panelled door and fanlight.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.  Retaining interior timber panelled shutters.  Stone steps leading to entrance door.

NAME: Clifton
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited attached four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1845.  Hipped artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and render eaves band.  Roughcast rendered walls with render plinth, quoins, string course between floors and moulded render surrounds to openings.  Segmental-arched opening with timber pilastered doorcase, cobweb fanlight and timber panelled door.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior shutters.  Octagonal cut-stone gate piers and timber gate to site.

Detached three-bay two-storey house, built 1846.  Hipped artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls.  Segmental-arched opening with timber pilaster doorcase, radial fanlight, sidelights and timber panelled door.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sill.  Retaining interior features.  Steps leading to entrance door.  Octagonal cut-stone piers with cast-iron gates set in rendered boundary walls.

Pair of semi-detached three-bay two-storey houses, built c. 1820.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with render quoins and moulded render surrounds with keystones to openings.  Segmental-arched door openings having timber pilaster doorcases, timber panelled doors, fanlights and sidelights.  Tripartite windows over doors.  Timber sliding sash and replacement uPVC windows.  Rendered boundary walls to site.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house with bay windows and projecting porch, built c. 1880, as part of a terrace of six.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with recessed panels under bay windows.  Chamfered corners and moulded cornice to porch.  Timber sliding sash windows, paired to porch.  Timber panelled internal shutters.  Cast-iron railings and rendered boundary walls to site.

Terraced five-bay single-storey house with bay windows flanking central door, built c. 1870, as part of a terrace of eight.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Hipped single-pitched roofs to bay windows.  Rendered walls with label mouldings over openings.  Segmental-arched door opening with timber pilastered doorcase, sidelights, fanlight, timber panelled door and stone threshold.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Rendered boundary walls and piers with timber gate to site.

NAME: Scott Mausoleum
COMPOSITION: Freestanding single-bay single-storey neo-Egyptian temple style mausoleum, dated 1837, comprising engaged Doric columns flanking recessed entrance with pediment above.  Pitched limestone cut-stone roof.  Cut-limestone walls with inset plaque to front elevation, having rubble stone side walls and plain frieze.  Carved limestone lugged doorcase with cast-iron double leaf doors.  Set in graveyard of ruined church.  Inscribed plaque reads ‘A.D. 1837 erected by John Bindon Scott of Cahercon and John Scott of Crevagh to the memory of their fathers also for themselves and posterity’.

NAME: Saint Michael's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan neo-Gothic  Roman Catholic church, built 1829, comprising gable-fronted entrance, three-bay side elevation and two-bay transepts.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone bellcote having cross finial and corner pinnacles to gables.  Cut-limestone walls to front elevation, rubble stone walls to remaining elevation, with cut-stone quoins and dressings to openings.  Inscribed plaque over entrance door and recessed blind plaques over transept doors.  Pointed arch openings with limestone sills and leaded coloured glass.  Tripartite window with limestone tracery and hood moulding to front elevation.  Four-centred arch door opening with moulded cut-stone doorcase, label moulding and timber double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features, including reredos, galleries and pierced decorative frieze.  Detached single-bay single-storey outbuilding and cut-stone piers to site.

NAME: J. O'Dea
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1890, with timber shopfront to ground floor.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with moulded render architraves to first floor.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking openings with fluted consoles, fascia, marbleised lettering and moulded cornice above.  Timber panelled double leaf doors with overlight and fixed window to shopfront.  Segmental-arched windows with timber sliding sash windows, having decorative tracery to upper panes.

NAME: Peadar Mac Fhlannchadha Memorial
COMPOSITION: Freestanding memorial, erected c. 1965, comprising stepped plinth and channelled cut-limestone pedestal with inset plaque surmounted by bronze bust.

NAME: The Curtain Shop
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1890, with timber shopfront to ground floor.  Pitched slate roof with brick chimneystacks and cast-iron gutter.  Rendered walls with render quoins and moulded render surrounds to upper floor openings.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking openings with consoles, fascia and moulded cornice above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber panelled double leaf doors with overlight and replacement display window to shopfront.

NAME: The Grove
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1870, with three-bay two-storey extension to rear, c. 1995.  Pitched artificial slate with red brick chimneystacks, gabled dormers having decorative timber bargeboards and wrought-iron finials.  Exposed rubble stone walls.  Paired timber sliding sash windows to ground floor.  Round-headed openings with timber sliding sash windows to first floor.  Timber panelled door with radial fanlight set in projected gabled glazed porch.  Timber panelled shutters to interior.  Rubble stone boundary walls and piers to site.

Detached three-bay two-storey Royal Irish Constabulary Barracks, built c. 1800, with single-bay two-storey extension to right, c. 1910, having attached single-bay two-storey extension, c. 1980.  Later used as Garda Station, now disused.  Pitched slate roof with moulded eaves course, rendered chimneystacks and bull nosed copings.  Hipped slate roof early twentieth century extension and flat roof to late twentieth century extension.  Roughcast render over rubble stone walls, with render quoins, render surrounds to openings and string course between floors having paired brackets over entrance door.  Recessed blind arches to early twentieth century extension.  Round-headed door opening set in recessed bay, with replacement timber door and fanlight, approached by limestone steps.  Round-headed blind arches with round-headed window openings to ground floor.  Timber sliding sash windows, in tripartite arrange over entrance door.  Coursed cut stone gate piers and hooped flat iron gates to site.

NAME: A. Ryan and Son Warehouse
COMPOSITION: Terraced four-bay four-storey mill, built c. 1870, comprising three-bay block with gabled single-bay block to right hand side.  Now disused.  Pitched slate roofs with cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rubble stone walls with cut-stone quoins, cast-iron tie plates and render name fascia with raised lettering below first floor openings.  Remains of hoist to gabled bay.  Various timber windows, shutters and cast-iron bars to window openings.  Timber matchboard doors to loading bay.

NAME: Clare Motor Rewinds
COMPOSITION: Detached double gable-fronted six-bay four-storey former mill, built c. 1875, with eight-bay side elevations.  Now in use as workshop to ground floor.  Pitched profiled metal sheet roof.  Rubble stone walls with render panel having raised lettering.  Various timber windows and shutters to window openings.  Timber matchboard doors to loading bays.  Single-pitched corrugated sheet canopy to yard.

NAME: Kilrush Heritage Centre
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey former market house, dated 1808, with breakfront end bays, former colonnade to ground floor and with curved central gablet having inset clock.  Cantilevered balustraded balcony with inset plaque to first floor.  In use as town hall in 1885, now in use as heritage centre and public service offices.  Hipped artificial slate roof with roughcast render to gablet and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with render quoins and string course between floors.  Cut-limestone walls and piers to ground floor, with voussoirs and keystones openings.  Replacement fittings to openings.

NAME: Manchester Martyrs Monument
COMPOSITION: Freestanding limestone cut-stone Hiberno-Romanesque style memorial, erected 1903, comprising cut-stone plinth, two-tier arcaded pedestal with plain and barley sugar columns, surmounted by carved limestone statue.  Inset plaques to lower section of pedestal and low relief portraits to upper section of pedestal.  Plaques inscribed in English, Irish and French.  Celtic strap work to column capitals.  Surrounded by cut-stone plinth with hooped railings.  Erected in memory of the Manchester Martyrs.

NAME: Lillis Travel
COMPOSITION: Attached three-bay three-storey cut-limestone former bank, built c. 1925, now in use as travel agents.  Roof not visible.  Recessed panels under ground floor windows, moulded chamfered surrounds to ground floor openings, string course with dentils between first and second floor, carved architraves to first floor, with eaves course and pediment above.  Stone sills and replacement uPVC windows to upper floor openings.  Timber panelled door with overlight and timber fixed windows to ground floor.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Saint Senan's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1840 to design by William Owen, comprising three-bay side elevation, single-bay transepts, single-bay single-storey flat-roofed crenellated side chapel to left hand side and pair of gable-fronted two-bay single-storey sacristies to rear.  Single-bay four-stage tower and octagonal cut-stone spire to left hand side of entrance, c. 1860 added by J.J.McCarthy.  Gabled porch addition to entrance gable.  Projecting porches added to transepts, c. 1990.  Pitched slate roof with cut-limestone copings.  Cut-limestone chimneystacks to sacristies.  Castellated parapet to tower and lucarnes to spire.  Snecked limestone walls with stepped buttresses and crenellated and corbelled parapets.  Rendered walls to rear.  Rusticated limestone walls and cut-stone quoins to transept porches.  Rose window with carved colonnette spokes and stained glass.  Round-headed openings with cut-stone surrounds and stained glass windows.  Tripartite window behind altar.  Romanesque-style entrance, comprising cut-limestone walls with engaged colonnettes and archivolts, surrounding recessed timber matchboards double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features including queen post truss timber roof structure with painted ceiling panels, cut-stone arcades to transepts and mosaic tiles to passageways between pews.  Stained glass by Barff and Clarke Studios. Cut-stone gate piers and plinth with cast-iron railings, wrought-iron lantern-holder and cut stone steps to site.  Celtic cross grave markers to priests’ graves.

NAME: Kilrush Community College
COMPOSITION: Detached ten-bay three-storey over basement rubble stone-built former convent, built c. 1860 to design by J.J.McCarthy, now in use as school.  Comprising seven-bay central block, flanked by gabled breakfront to left hand side and gabled projecting chapel to right hand side.  Gabled two-bay recessed block to left hand side.  Seven-bay two-storey return.  Detached six-bay two-storey school, built c. 1900, with single-bay advanced end bays and recessed single-bay to left.  Pitched slate roofs with cut-stone bellcote, chimneystacks, gable copings and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Snecked limestone walls with cut-stone plinth and quoins.  Pointed arch opening with haunched doorcase, carved and cut-stone dressings, sidelights, divided fanlight and timber matchboard double leaf doors with wrought-iron strap hinges, approached by flight of steps.  Trefoil-headed openings to first floor, haunched openings to ground and second floors, with cut-limestone dressings and timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.  Segmental-arched cut-limestone gate with cross finial above, set in dressed stone walls having cut-stone copings.

NAME: Community Centre
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay single- and two-storey former school, built c. 1875, comprising four-bay single-storey block with gabled porch and advanced gabled two-storey bay to left hand side.  Four-bay two-storey extension added to rear, c. 1980.  Now in use as community centre.  Pitched slate roofs with cut-stone chimneystacks and gable copings with cross finials.  Snecked limestone walls with cut-stone quoins.  Chamfered stone sills and lintels to replacement windows, in tripartite arrangement to main block, and in bipartite arrangement to gabled bay and porch.  Rubble stone boundary walls with cut-stone gate piers to site.

NAME: FAS
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey former vocational school, built c. 1935, with recessed central three-bay block having stepped pediment and recessed porch to ground floor.  Now in use as training centre.  Flat roof with parapet and pediment.  Rendered walls with moulded architraves to ground floor and having lintel over first floor openings.  Render panel with lettering between ground and first floors.  Pediment over central tripartite opening to first floor.  Timber half glazed double leaf doors flanked by sidelights.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.  Rendered boundary walls with wrought-iron gates and railings to site.

NAME: Saint Senan's Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Church of Ireland church, dated 1813, comprising three-bay nave with lean-to vestry and three-stage entrance tower, added c. 1840.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone gable copings.  Single-pitched roof to vestry.  Cut-stone crenellations and pinnacles to tower.  Rubble stone walls with cut-stone string courses and quoins to upper stage of tower.  Pointed arch openings with limestone dressings and tracery to nave.  Pointed arch and square-headed openings to tower with cast-iron quarry glazing, label mouldings to second stage openings and having louvers to third stage openings.  Pointed arch door opening with flush metal door.   Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers and mausolea.  Cut-stone piers with cast-iron gates and wrought-iron lamp holder.

NAME: Kilrush House
COMPOSITION: Remains of Kilrush House and Vandeleur Estate, built 1808.  Kilrush House, burnt 1897.  Detached three-bay single-storey coursed rubble stone gate lodge with single-bay single-storey limestone cut-stone gabled projecting porch to centre, flanked by open verandas with limestone cut-stone octagonal-profile columns.  Gateway with four limestone cut-stone piers having neo-Egyptian-style panelled piers and cast-iron gates.  Section of rubble stone walled garden with segmental-arch opening having bellcote above.  Gateway with six cut-stone piers having rubble stone curved walls and cast-iron gates.

NAME: Saunders
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1800, shopfront inserted, c. 1900.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with render quoins and moulded architraves to upper floors.  Timber shopfront comprising chamfered and panelled pilasters flanking fixed windows and timber panelled doors with overlights, having carved consoles, fascia, marbleised lettering and moulded cornice above.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Broderick's
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay two-storey over basement house, built c. 1870, with shopfront to ground floor.  Pitched artificial slate roof.  Rendered walls with quoins and moulded architraves to first floor.  Shopfront comprising chamfered pilasters flanking timber panelled doors with overlights and timber fixed windows, having moulded consoles, fascia and moulded cornice above.  Segmental-arched openings with timber sliding sash windows to first floor.  Timber panelled shutters to interior.

NAME: O'Sullivan
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1800, shopfront inserted, c. 1930.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with render quoins and moulded render architraves to upper floors.  Timber shopfront comprising panelled pilasters flanking fixed windows and timber panelled doors with overlights having consoles, fascia, lettering and cornice above.  Timber sliding sash windows to upper floors.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Kilrush Courthouse
COMPOSITION: Attached four-bay two-storey court house, built c. 1830, with central round-headed door opening and seven-bay two-storey return.  Hipped artificial slate roof with rendered parapet having cut-stone copings and eaves cornice.  Rendered walls with cut-stone quoins and moulded limestone architraves to first floor openings.  Gibbsian surround and timber panelled double leaf doors to round-headed door opening.  Segmental-arched door opening with timber panelled door and overlight.  Segmental-arched openings to ground floor and square-headed openings to first floor with timber casement windows.

NAME: Glynn Marine Supplies
COMPOSITION: Pair of gable-fronted three-bay five- and six-storey former mills, built c. 1820, with thirteen-bay side elevations and castellated parapets.  Six-bay two-storey infill block to centre, c. 1870.  Attached single-bay single-storey battlemented screen walls to left and right.  Freestanding single-bay five-storey silo, c. 1960.  Now partly in use as retail outlet.  Pitched slate roofs with rubble stone crenellated parapets.  Flue behind parapet to left building.  Rubble stone walls with string courses to parapets and render to lower levels.  Mass concrete walls to rear.  Corrugated-sheet cladding to silo.  Hoist in position to central bays.  Round-headed blind arches to top floor of left hand side building.  Square-headed openings with timber sliding sash windows and boarded shutters.  Central loading bay openings with timber matchboard doors to right hand side building.  Steel windows to ground floor infill building.

End-of-terrace two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1820, with bay window and canopy to ground floor.  Rendered chimneystacks and moulded parapet to roof.  Carved timber consoles to hipped canopy.  Rendered walls with render quoins, decorative frieze to eaves and moulded render architraves to upper floor openings.  Segmental-arched door opening having Ionic columns flanking timber panelled door with moulded lintel and fanlight above, approached by flight of steps.  Replacement uPVC windows.  Wrought-iron railings to site.

NAME: Internet Bureau
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay four-storey former hotel, built c. 1820, subsequently used as Sisters of Mercy orphanage, in use as Christian Brothers School in 1874 and now in use as private house.  Rendered chimneystack and moulded roof parapet.  Cut-limestone walls with string course to ground floor.  Rendered walls with render quoins, decorative frieze and architraves to upper floors.  Decorative render pediment over central first floor opening.  Round-headed opening with timber panelled door and plain fanlight.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.  Cast-iron railings to site.

Corner-sited attached gable-fronted two-bay five-storey former mill, built c. 1800, with twelve-bay side elevations having gabled loading bay and nine-bay four-storey return.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Rendered walls to gable front, rubble stone walls to sides and rear.  Blocked windows and timber doors.

NAME: Vandaleur Mausoleum
STREET1: Saint Senan's Church of Ireland Graveyard
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted three-bay single-storey limestone cut-stone mausoleum, built 1873, with five-bay side elevations.  Design attributed to William Fogerty.  Pitched Liscannor flagged roof with cut-stone gable copings having finial Celtic crosses and skew blocks.  Cut-limestone walls with blind arcades having engaged columns, clustered colonnettes to corners and inset roundel to gable.

NAME: Fanore Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch coursed rubble limestone road bridge over Murrough river, built c. 1850, with cut-stone voussoirs.

NAME: The Bridge Hostel
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan three-bay two-storey former Garda Station, built 1932, with advanced central porch and two-bay return having attached glazed porch.  Now in use as hostel.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with recessed arches over ground floor windows, render quoins and moulded cornice to porch parapet.  Replacement timber windows and timber panelled door.  Retaining interior features.  Detached four-bay single-storey outbuilding to rear.

NAME: Black Head Lighthouse
COMPOSITION: Freestanding square-plan single-bay two-storey lighthouse with metal-framed glazed lantern, built 1936.  Constructed by Robert McDonald of Galway.  Flat concrete roof with light enclosed in riveted metal-framed glazed housing and surrounding by tubular iron railing balustrade.  Rendered walls.  Timber matchboard door.  Set on concrete plinth.  Approached by concrete path and steps.

NAME: Tobercornan Well
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Gothic Revival single-bay single-storey well house over spring, built c. 1860.  Corbelled rubble stone roof with dressed stone gable copings and corner pinnacles.  Squared stone walls with corner buttresses.  Pointed arch door opening with limestone threshold. Functioned as main water supply for Ballyvaughan in times of drought.

Freestanding public fountain, erected 1875, comprising carved limestone plinth and capped pedestal with inset plaques and cast-iron lion head spouts having troughs below. Plaques record the names of those involved in providing Ballyvaughan with one of the earliest reliable public water supplies in the country. The fountain was erected  by two Connemara stonemasons, the Coyne brothers, who were marooned in Ballyvaughan when their craft sank at Gleninagh pier.

NAME: Saint John the Baptist's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Gothic Revival Roman Catholic church, built 1858-66, with eight-bay side elevations, gable-fronted three-bay chancel, two-bay single-storey sacristy and two-stage entrance tower and spire.  Pitched concrete tile roof with gable copings, finials and cast-iron downpipes.  Cut-limestone spire with lucarnes.  Snecked limestone walls with stepped buttresses, string course, eaves dentils and some hood mouldings.  Pointed arch openings with cut-limestone dressings and cast-iron quarry clear and coloured glazing.  Retaining interior features.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers.  Cut-stone piers to front with cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: J. M. Mooney and Sons
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1850, with render shopfront inserted, c. 1900.  No longer in commercial use to ground floor.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with moulded render architraves.  Shopfront comprising panelled end pilasters with fluted consoles, fascia, lettering and moulded cornice.  Replacement fittings to openings.

NAME: Finavarra Point Martello Tower
COMPOSITION: Freestanding ovoid-plan single-bay two-stage  Martello Tower, built c. 1810, with three gun placements to roof parapet.    Cut-limestone flat roof with parapet, trefoil-plan radial-pattern gun mounts having metal pivots and circular rails.  Battered cut-limestone walls with plinth.  Murder hole to entrance soffit.  Brick vaulted interior roof structure.  Brick magazine with inset glazed candle boxes to interior.  Steps leading to roof.  Detached outbuilding to site.  Freestanding War Department stone inscribed ‘WD/No XIII'.

NAME: Caherbaneagh Village
COMPOSITION: Former clachan, comprising group of detached three-bay single-storey rubble stone-built houses, built c. 1775.  Abandoned, c. 1845-1848, now ruinous.  Rubble stone walls.  Square-headed openings with stone sills and lintels.

NAME: Comerford mausoleum
COMPOSITION: Freestanding single-bay two-storey cut-stone-built Comerford mausoleum, built c. 1865, comprising rusticated underground burial chamber, channelled walls with pilasters above, surmounted by cut-stone obelisk having ball finial and surrounded by cast-iron railings. Remains of freestanding rubble stone-built single-cell church, built c. 1500.  Now ruinous.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers and mausolea, c. 1700 - present.

NAME: Mount Vernon Lodge
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1790, with single-bay full-height bowed section to centre.  Now in use as guest house.  Single-bay single-storey lean-to porch to left side elevation.  Single-bay single-storey linking bay to right.  Single-bay two-storey return.  Single-bay two-storey extension to rear, c. 1990.  Pitched slate roofs with roughcast rendered chimneystacks.  Conical artificial slate roof to bow.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Timber sliding sash windows, in pairs to ground floor.  Round-headed door opening with timber panelled door, curved cut-stone lintel and fanlight.  Walled garden to left.  Liscannor paved yard to rear.  Rubble stone single-pitched roofed outbuilding to rear.  Former stables and coach house converted to residential use.  Former holiday house of Lady Gregory.

NAME: Finavarra House
COMPOSITION: Remains of detached L-plan three-bay two-storey over basement house with dormer attic, built c. 1825, having three-bay three-storey return to rear.  Now in ruins.  Venetian door opening to ground floor.  Group of detached multiple-bay single-storey outbuildings forming yard, now in ruins.  Detached three-bay single-storey gate lodge with single-bay flat-roofed projecting porch to centre, now derelict.  Detached three-bay single-storey gate lodge, now in ruins.  Freestanding single-bay single-storey rubble stone folly, now in ruins.  Cast-iron and cut-stone piers with wrought-iron gates.

NAME: Abbey House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820, with two-bay single-storey extension to rear, c. 1985.  Hipped slate roof with cut-stone chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with render quoins and render surround to entrance door.  Timber sliding sash windows with external shutter additions.  Replacement timber panelled door.  Detached four-bay single-storey outbuilding with half-dormer attic to site.  Cut-stone piers having cast-iron gates and stile.

NAME: Muckinish Castle
COMPOSITION: Remains of freestanding square-plan single-bay four-storey rubble stone-built tower house, built c. 1450, now in ruins.  Random rubble stone walls with base batter and battlements and machicolations to parapet.  Square-headed windows and gun loops.  Bawn wall partially rebuilt.

NAME: Saint Patrick's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1938-39, with six-bay nave elevation.  Pitched slate roof with rendered bellcote and cross finial.  Roughcast rendered walls with render plat bands and surrounds to openings, and inscribed foundation stone. Breakfront gabled porch with cross finial and round-headed door opening.  Recessed timber matchboard double leaf doors with blank fanlight and plaque above, flanked by square-headed replacement windows and having stained glass oculus above.  Round-headed openings with replacement windows.  Retaining interior features including arched chancel screen, organ loft with panelled timber balustrade, exposed roof timbers and marble memorial from earlier church.  Statue of Blessed Virgin Mary and kneeling children to site.  Rubble stone boundary walls with crenellated copings and cut-stone piers.

NAME: Ballyvelaghan School (former)
COMPOSITION: Detached cruciform-plan former school, dated 1861, comprising four-bay block flanked by three-bay gabled breakfronts entrance blocks.  Now in use as house.  Hipped and pitched artificial slate roofs with cut-stone copings and chimneystacks.  Replacement ridge crestings and rainwater goods.  Cut-limestone walls with plinth and inscribed plaque.  Cut-stone sills and lintels to replacement windows.  Replacement timber panelled doors.  Detached single-bay single-storey rubble stone-built lean-to outbuilding.  Rubble stone-built boundary walls with cut-stone piers having pyramidal cappings.

NAME: Aughinish Martello Tower
COMPOSITION: Freestanding ovoid-plan single-bay three-stage former Martello Tower, c. 1810.  Now in use as house.  Flat glass roof with cut-limestone parapet and cut-stone chimneystacks.   Battered cut-limestone walls with plinth.  External metal stairs leading to entrance.  Square-headed openings with replacement timber casement windows.  Replacement timber matchboard door.

NAME: Gregan's Castle Hotel
COMPOSITION: Detached six-bay two-storey house, built c. 1750, with half-octagonal lower projection.  Extended  c. 1840, with single-bay two-storey gabled projecting bay and single-storey flat-roofed projecting bay to front.  Seven-bay two-storey wing with single-storey canted bay windows to ground floor, added c. 1990, to accommodate use as hotel.  Hipped and pitched artificial slate roofs with cut-stone and rendered chimneystacks.  Flat roofs to various additions.  Painted rubble stone walls to left hand side, rendered walls with quoins to right hand side.  Timber casement and timber sliding sash windows with render label mouldings.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-stone piers, c. 1850, with cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Newtown Art College
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey former house, built c. 1820, with single-bay two-storey return and lean-to end bay to left.  Single-bay single-storey rubble stone built lean-to added to rear, c. 1995.  Now in use as college.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Round-headed door opening with cut-stone block-and-start surround, replacement timber panelled door and fanlight.  Replacement timber windows with stone sills.  Detached U-plan multiple-bay single- and two-storey rubble stone building, built c. 1995, incorporating fabric of earlier outbuildings, built c. 1820.  Freestanding, renovated, circular-plan  five-stage tower house, built c. 1550, with base batter, battlemented roof parapet and machicolation.  Renovated c.1994.  Pair of cast-iron water pumps to site, now in use as flower pots.

NAME: Ailwee Cave Visitor Centre
COMPOSITION: Freeform plan  two-storey rubble stone-clad visitor centre, completed 1979, with recessed upper floor.  Designed by A. and D. Wejchert as entrance to natural cave system.  Flat concrete roofs with rubble stone parapets.  Roof to ground floor rises to form ramp to first floor.  Coursed rubble stone clad walls.  Square-headed openings with timber fixed windows, stone sills and lintels.  Concrete lintel over door opening with glazed timber panelled double leaf doors and sidelights.  Set into natural caves with artificial terrace to front forming car park.  Detached single-bay single-storey ticket office.  Detached seven-bay single-storey rubble stone-built outbuilding, built c. 1980, with two-bay recessed end bay to left, now in use as restaurant.  Detached circular-plan single-bay single-storey rubble stone-built dovecote, built c. 1990, with conical roof.

NAME: Kelly's
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay single-storey thatched house with dormer attic, built c. 1825.  Hipped reed thatch with rendered chimneystack and concrete copings.  Rendered walls.  Replacement timber sliding sash windows.  Replacement timber panelled door with overlight.  Detached two-bay single-storey rubble stone outbuilding with segmental-headed opening.  Detached two-bay single-storey lean-to outbuilding.  Cut-stone piers with wrought-iron gates.

Detached four-bay single-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1850.  Pitched Moher flagged roof with rendered chimneystacks and render gable copings.  Rubble stone walls, partly rendered.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber matchboard door with overlight.  Attached single-bay single-storey lean-to advanced outbuildings to left and to right.

NAME: Fisherstreet Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch coursed limestone road bridge over river, built c. 1850, with cut-stone voussoirs.

NAME: Killilagh Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1820, with gable-fronted single-bay entrance elevation, four-bay side elevation and two-bay transepts.  Pitched artificial slate roof with finials and gable copings.  Rendered walls.  Pointed arch door opening having moulded limestone ogee-headed surround.  Trefoil opening with cut-limestone dressings and hood moulding over entrance door.  Narrow lancet openings with leaded glass, set in paired arrangement to transepts and in tripartite arrangement to chancel.

NAME: Ballyinalacken House Hotel
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey over basement house, built c. 1840, with bowed central bay, octagonal-plan projecting end bay to right hand side and two-bay return with canted bay window.  Seven-bay single-storey wing on an L-shaped plan, added c. 1990, to accommodate use as hotel.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and moulded eaves cornice.  Conical roof to bowed bay and pyramidal roof to octagonal bay.  Rendered walls with rusticated quoins.  Pediments over openings and dentilated cornice to octagonal-plan bay.  Replacement windows and doors.  Retaining interior features.  Freestanding single-bay four-stage tower house to site, built c. 1550, now in ruins.  Cut-stone piers with iron gates and railings.

NAME: Toomaghera Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1860, comprising four-bay nave with gabled entrance porch and having recessed chancel.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone copings, corbels and cross finials.  Snecked cut-limestone walls with plinth.  Roughcast rendered walls to rear and end gable.  Chamfered limestone door surround with pair of timber doors.  Pointed arch openings with moulded limestone surrounds and replacement windows.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers.  Ashlar gate piers to front.

NAME: Roadford Bridge
COMPOSITION: Six-arch rubble stone road bridge over river, built c. 1810, with cut-stone voussoirs and cutwaters.

NAME: Doonnagore Castle
COMPOSITION: Freestanding circular-plan single-bay three-stage tower house, built c. 1500.  Ruined in 1916, extensively reconstructed, c. 1970.  In use as private residence. Slate conical roof with metal finial.  Rubble stone walls with base batter, battlemented roof parapet and machicolation.  Gun loop openings.  Round-headed door opening.  Rubble stone bawn enclosure.  Cut-stone piers to front with iron gates.

NAME: Doolin Bridge
COMPOSITION: Twelve-span trabeated rubble stone road bridge over river, built c. 1775, with two  pedestrian refuges, cut-stone cutwaters, lintels and limestone parapet walls.  Concrete replacement slabs spanning five bays to right-hand side of upstream elevation.

NAME: Saint Mochua's  Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height church, built c. 1840, with gabled entrance porch, bellcote, six-bay nave elevations, advanced confessional and projecting sacristy.  Originally Church of Ireland church sited at Ballyvaughan, dismantled and reconstructed as a Roman Catholic church on present site, 1943.  Pitched slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods, gable copings and cut-stone bellcote.  Chimneystack to sacristy.  Snecked limestone walls with quoins.  Lancet openings with cut-stone architraves and replacement uPVC windows.  Pointed arch opening with cut-stone architrave, timber matchboard door and strap hinges.  Cut-stone gate piers set in irregular coursed stone walls to site.

NAME: Hollywell House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1790, with four-bay two-storey return.  Top floor reputedly removed, c. 1910.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone chimneystacks and gable copings.  Lime-washed rubble stone walls.  Round-headed door opening flanked by sidelights with cut-limestone Gibbsian surround and timber panelled door.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.  Detached four-bay single-storey rubble stone-built outbuilding and cut-stone piers with moulded cappings to site.  Cobbled yard to rear.

NAME: Ballykeel House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey over basement house, built c. 1800, with three-bay full-height bowed central section front and rear elevations.  Hipped artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and moulded eaves course.  Cut-limestone walls with raised architraves, aprons to ground floor windows and string course at sill level first floor of bow.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Tuscan columns flanking timber panelled door with simple entablature above.  Curved cut-limestone walls to basement area and to steps leading to entrance.  Retaining interior features.  Four cast-iron chute covers to cellars with high relief motifs.  Flagged basement area with cut-stone vaulted recesses in external retaining wall.  Detached single-bay two-storey gable-fronted outbuilding with pinnacles and eight-bay side elevations.  Detached four-bay single-storey byre with segmental-arched openings.  Freestanding two-bay single-storey folly with lancet openings, now in ruins.  Gateway to front comprising four cut-limestone piers and pair of square-headed pedestrian gates set in curved walls.

NAME: Fanta Deanery
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey former glebe house, built c. 1790, with central porch and single-bay single-storey return.  Now in use as private house.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and gable copings.  Roughcast rendered walls with slate hanging to gables.  Cut stone walls to porch.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-stone gate piers with iron gates to site.

NAME: Ballyshanny House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1810, with two-bay single-storey flanking wings.  Renovated internally, c. 1850.  Flat-roofed projecting glazed porch added to front, c. 1960.  Pitched Moher flagged roof with cut-stone chimneystacks and gable copings.  Roughcast rendered walls with string course at sill level first floor.  Replacement timber windows.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-limestone piers with cast-iron gates to site.

NAME: Noughaval Market Stone
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cut-stone market stone, erected c. 1725, comprising octagonal-profile pier set on a stepped plinth and with tapered cap.

NAME: Saint Columba's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1861, with gable to roadside, four-bay nave elevations, two-bay single-storey porch to right and two-bay single-storey sacristy to rear.  Pitched slate roof with cross finial and bellcote.  Roughcast rendered walls with render plat bands.  Leaded glass with timber Y-tracery set in lancet openings.  Pointed arch and square-headed door openings with timber matchboard doors having wrought-iron strap hinges.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-stone stone gate piers with moulded caps, set in rendered boundary walls.

NAME: Glenquin House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1860, with two-bay two-storey return and attached single-bay single-storey outbuilding to rear.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and cut-stone eaves course.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Segmental-arched door opening with timber panelled door, fanlight and sidelights.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.  Cast-iron piers with cast-iron gates and railings to site.

NAME: All Saints Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1850, with three-bay side elevations.  Lean-to bay added to rear, c. 1995.  Pitched artificial slate roof with aluminium rainwater goods and cross finial.  Cut-limestone entrance front with roughcast rendered walls to sides and rendered walls to rear.  Pointed arch opening with cut-limestone surround and replacement timber panelled double leaf doors.  Lancet windows with leaded coloured glass.  Tripartite window arrangement to entrance and chancel elevations.  Chancel openings partly blocked to accommodate reredos.  Retaining interior features.  Inscribed stone plaque in church "This monument was erected by a few of the parishioners of Kilkeedy in memory of their P.P., the Rev. Podl who died Sept 27th. 1836 requiscat in pace amen". Freestanding concrete belfry to site comprising square-profile columns with domed roof and concrete statue.  Remains of cut-stone bellcote, c. 1850, to site.

NAME: M. O'Grady
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1890, originally two-bay two-storey thatched post office, now also in use as public house.  Renovated and extended to right, c. 1940, with render pubfront inserted to left ground floor.  Extended to right, c. 1970, with two-bay single-storey annexe added to left.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks, concrete gable copings and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with render quoins and moulded render architraves.  Render shopfront comprising paired pilasters flanking openings with vermiculated capital panels, lettering and moulded cornice above.  Chamfered reveals to openings with replacement fittings.  Attached garage, built c. 1970, to right.  Petrol pump to front.

NAME: Bleach Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch cut-limestone road bridge over river, built c. 1840, with voussoirs and coursed limestone parapet walls.

NAME: Seamount House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey gate lodge, built c. 1810, with gabled advanced central entrance bay.  Hipped Moher flagged roof with rendered chimneystack.  Rendered walls with label mouldings over openings.  Paired timber sliding sash windows and timber panelled door.  Canted bay window to side elevation.  Gateway to front comprising eight cut-stone piers with curved walls and cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: O'Brien's Column
COMPOSITION: Freestanding limestone cut-stone monument, erected 1853, comprising fluted Doric column surmounted by an urn and set on a square-profile plinth with inscribed plaques.

NAME: Saint Brigid's School
COMPOSITION: Detached H-plan five-bay single-storey former school, built c. 1845, comprising three recessed central bays with veranda and gablet, flanked by gabled and canted end bays.  Now in use as pair of houses with dormer attic and rear porch additions.  Pitched slate roofs with rendered chimneystacks and decorative bargeboards.  Rendered walls with label mouldings over openings and inset plaques over door openings.  Cast-iron columns to veranda.  Clock set in brick surround to gable.  Timber and uPVC windows with stone sills.  Cut-limestone block-and-start chamfered doorcase with timber matchboard door.  Octagonal cut-stone gate piers and iron gate to site set in painted stone wall.

Freestanding single-bay single-storey Gothic Revival well house, built c. 1820.  Stone flagged flat roof with cut-stone crenellated parapet and central finial.  Dressed stone walls with string course and carved stone plaque.  Pointed arch opening with cut-limestone surround and remains of wrought-iron gate.

NAME: Birchfield House
COMPOSITION: Gateway, built c. 1800, comprising four cut-stone piers set in curved rubble stone walls having pair of square-headed pedestrian gates and cast-iron double leaf gates. Detached three-bay single-storey gate lodge, built c. 1800, now in ruins.  Remains of detached five-bay two- and three-storey rubble stone-built Gothic Revival house, built by Cornelius O’Brien MP c. 1800, now in ruins.  Group of detached multiple-bay single-storey outbuildings to site, now in ruins.

NAME: Saint Bridget's Well
COMPOSITION: Holy well, built c. 1830.  Detached single-bay single-storey lean-to building.  Liscannor flagged single-pitched roof with concrete coping, rendered chimneystacks, and having timber beams to flat roof over corridor to well.  Rendered and rubble stone wall.  Timber matchboard door to building.  Segmental-arched opening to well.  Numerous votive offerings to interior.  Stream falls over Liscannor flags to well.

NAME: O'Brien's Tower
COMPOSITION: Freestanding dressed stone Gothic Revival style folly, built 1835, comprising circular-plan single-bay two-stage tower with battered base to centre and battlemented roof parapet, flanked by circular-plan single-bay two-storey lower tower to left and single-bay single-storey battlemented screen wall to right having segmental-arched door opening.  Built by Cornelius O’Brien M.P. Spectacularly sited on the Cliffs of Moher.

NAME: Saint Augustine's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1893, with two-bay gable front having projecting entrance porch, four-bay nave elevations, transept to right and sacristy to left.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone bellcote, finials and gable copings.  Rendered walls with buttresses, string courses and plat bands.  Lancet openings with timber sliding sash windows.  Pointed arch door openings with timber double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Rubble stone boundary walls to site with cut-stone gate piers and cast-iron gates.

NAME: O'Brien's Bridge
COMPOSITION: Triple-arch cut-stone stone road bridge over estuary of river Inagh, dated 1836, with voussoirs, single and paired pilasters and V-cutwaters.

NAME: Sandfield Lodge
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay single-storey house, built c. 1775.  Originally three-bay with round-headed door opening to centre and two-storey rear elevation.  Extended, c. 1820, with single-bay single-storey flanking wings.  Renovated, c. 1880, with three-bay single-storey open arcaded porch added to front.  Pitched and hipped slate roofs with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls.  Replacement fittings to openings.  Retaining interior features.
Harbour comprising pair of cut-stone enclosing piers, built c. 1830, and c. 1880.  Cast-iron lamp standards, bollards and inset ladders.

NAME: Saint Brigid's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1858, comprising four-bay nave with central gabled entrance porch.  Three-bay single-storey sacristy added to rear, c. 1985.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cross finials and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Cut-stone copings to porch roof.  Snecked stone walls.  Cut-stone quoins to porch.  Rendered walls to rear.  Timber matchboard door.  Lancet windows with timber Y-tracery and leaded stained glass.  Tripartite window to west gable.  Retaining interior features including raked galleries, clustered cast-iron piers and carved marble altar.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers.  Octagonal cut-stone piers with moulded cappings and cast-iron gates.

NAME: New Bridge
COMPOSITION: Triple-arch road bridge over river, built c. 1840.  Irregularly coursed stone walls with cut-stone voussoirs, double-keystones, U-cutwaters, end piers and copings.  Concrete pipes and casings to upstream side of bridge.

NAME: Saint Fachanan's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan Roman Catholic church, built c. 1865, comprising gable-fronted entrance with projecting porch, rose window and bellcote, three-bay side elevations, single-bay transepts and chancel to rear having two-bay single-storey sacristy.  Pitched artificial slate roof with clay crestings, cross finials, concrete copings, cut-stone bellcote and cast-iron downpipe.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with render quoins.  Carved limestone rose window with hood moulding and stained glass.  Round-headed door opening with raised render surround, timber matchboard door and fanlight.  Lancet windows with leaded coloured glass.  Retaining interior features.  Rendered boundary walls with cast-iron double leaf gates.  Wheel guards to corners.

NAME: Kilfenora Cathedral
COMPOSITION: Freestanding crow-stepped gable-fronted Church of Ireland cathedral, built from 1170-1200, incorporating fabric of earlier buildings.  Four-bay side elevations with single-bay recessed chancel to rear, having single-bay vestry to left.  In ruins in 1840 and reconstructed c. 1850.  Chancel and vestry now in ruins.  Pitched artificial slate roof with bellcote having pyramidal capping and flanking finials.  Rubble stone walls with slight batter to gable front.  Lancet openings with cut-stone dressings and timber sliding sash and fixed windows.  Pointed arch door opening with timber cut-limestone dressings, hood moulding and timber panelled door.  Retaining interior features.  Graveyard to site with various grave markers.  Rubble stone boundary walls.

NAME: Church of Saint Attracta
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1870, with three-bay nave elevation, polygonal chancel and sacristy to rear.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered bellcote and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls.  Round-headed openings with timber framed windows and concrete sills.  Retaining interior features including marble altar and timber altar rails.  Rendered boundary walls to site with stiles and gates.

NAME: Clifden House
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey over basement house, built c. 1800.  Hipped artificial slate roof with cut-stone chimneystacks.  Lime rendered walls with blind niche over entrance.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Carved limestone doorcase comprising engaged Tuscan columns flanking moulded architrave and timber panelled door, having entablature with rosettes above.  Retaining interior features.  Attached eight-bay single-storey stable range with half-dormer attic to right, now in use as house.  Detached two-bay three-storey gable-fronted former mill to site, now in ruins.  Cast-iron piers with wrought-iron gates to site.

NAME: Adelphi House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay single-storey over part-raised basement house, built c. 1810, with three-bay recessed central block having tripartite window openings and single-bay advanced end bays having relieving arches.  L-plan two-bay two-storey return to rear.  Hipped artificial slate roof with four diagonally placed chimneystacks and deep eaves with exposed timber rafters.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Slate hanging to west walls.  Glass lens set in wall beside front door step allowing view up from basement.  Timber pilasters and cornice to timber panelled door with overlight.  Diamond pane cast-iron windows set in cut-stone frames.  Tripartite windows flanking door.  Bow window to right side elevation.  Retaining interior shutters.  Detached two-bay single-storey gable-fronted rubble stone-built coach house to site.  Cut-stone gate piers with cast-iron gates to site.

NAME: Ballyportry Castle
COMPOSITION: Freestanding single-bay four-stage tower house, built c. 1530. Restored by architect Bob Brown (1926-84) in the late sixties and early seventies. Now in use as private house.  Slated roof.  Rubble stone walls with battered base, cut-stone quoins and castellated parapet with machicolation.  Inset plaque.  Pointed arch or square-headed openings with cut-stone dressings and steel windows.  Pointed arch opening with chamfered cut-stone surround and timber panelled door.  Remains of wall paintings. Rubble stone bawn wall with gunloop slits and diametrically opposing circular turrets c.1625 with steel gate to entrance.

NAME: Saint Joseph's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height former Roman Catholic church, built c. 1850, with three-bay nave and porch to right gable.  Now in use as outbuilding.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone bellcote, cast-iron rainwater goods and cut-stone gable copings.  Roughcast rendered walls with cast-iron tie plates.  Lancet openings with timber Y-tracery and stone sills.  Square-headed opening inserted, c. 1975, to accommodate use as outbuilding.  Rubble stone boundary walls to site.

NAME: Poplar Bridge
COMPOSITION: Double-arch rubble stone hump-back road bridge over river, built c. 1810, with cut-stone voussoirs.

NAME: Coad Church
COMPOSITION: Remains of freestanding single-cell three-bay single-storey rubble stone church, built c. 1500.  Renovated, c. 1750, with cut-stone bellcote inserted over left gable.  Now in ruins.  Various pointed arch, ogee-headed, round-headed and square-headed openings.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers and mausolea, c. 1750-present.  Cut-stone piers with wrought-iron gates set in rubble stone boundary walls to site.

NAME: Saint Cronan's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted Roman Catholic church, built c. 1820, with three-bay side elevation having single-bay transepts.  Gabled projecting porches added to transepts, c. 1920.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone bellcote and cross finial.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Pointed arch openings with timber Y-tracery.  Four-centred arch door opening with timber double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-stone gate piers with wrought-iron double leaf gates set in snecked stone boundary walls to site.

NAME: Saint Michael's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1850, comprising gabled entrance front with flat-roofed porch, four-bay side elevations and two-bay sacristy to rear.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered eaves band and carved limestone bellcote.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Lancet openings with leaded glass widows.  Y-tracery to gable window.  Retaining interior features included tiled floor, mosaic flooring, raked gallery and marble altar. Rusticated concrete block boundary walls with rendered piers and spear headed gates to site.

NAME: Church of the Immaculate Conception
COMPOSITION: Freestanding L-plan Roman Catholic church, built c. 1860, with three-bay range to rear.  Corner porch added in 1976.  Pitched artificial slate roofs with aluminium rainwater goods.  Canopy over entrance.  Roughcast rendered walls with render plat bands.  Pointed window openings with fixed pane timber windows.  Timber glazed entrance doors.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Bunshoon Bridge
COMPOSITION: Five-arch cut-stone road bridge over river Graney, built c. 1820, with cut-stone voussoirs, cutwaters and buttresses.  Renovated, c. 1960, with one arch remodelled.

NAME: Aughaderreen Bridge
COMPOSITION: Four-arch road bridge over river, built c. 1850, with arches of differing heights, form and date.  Parapet walls rebuilt, c. 1995.  Rubble stone walls with rebuilt and repointed sections.  Rendered capping to V-cutwaters.  Double irregularly coursed voussoirs to eastern arch, single course of cut limestone voussoirs to remaining arches.  Slightly pointed western arch.

NAME: Whitegate Fitted Furniture
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height former Roman Catholic church, built 1874, with four-bay side elevations and single-storey lean-to sacristy to rear.  Deconsecrated and extended to left, c.1970, with gable-fronted double-height replica, to accommodate use as factory.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone bellcote.  Rendered walls with quoins.  Lancet openings with timber Y-tracery and leaded stained glass.  Entrance altered to accommodate use as factory.

NAME: Meelick House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with four giant pilasters to front elevation.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Limestone doorcase comprising pilasters flanking timber panelled door and overlight with entablature above.  Detached L-plan single-bay single-storey gable-fronted rubble stone outbuilding to site.  Dressed stone gate piers and stile to site.

Detached three-bay two-storey former R.I.C. barracks, built c. 1880, now in use as private house.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Exposed rubble stone walls with rendered walls to sides and rear.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Segmental-arched opening with timber panelled door and plain fanlight.  Circular-profile gate piers with moulded cappings to site.

NAME: Saint Mary's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1870, with five-bay side elevation.  Two-bay single-storey sacristy added to rear, c. 1910.  Flat roof porch added to entrance gable, c. 1970.  Pitched slate roof with render gable copings, cross finial and bellcote.  Rendered walls with buttresses and plat bands.  Lancet openings with stone sills and timber sliding sash windows having inset quatrefoil to point.  Tudor arch door opening with timber glazed double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Moy House
COMPOSITION: Detached H-plan five-bay single-storey house, built c. 1830, comprising three-bay recessed central block with single-bay gabled projecting end bays having canted bay windows to both facades.  Renovated, c. 1860, with three-bay single-storey lean-to veranda added to front and single-bay three-storey Italianate tower added to rear.  Pitched and hipped slate roofs with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls.  Detached single-bay single-storey gable-fronted coach house to site.  Cut-stone piers with cast-iron gates to site.

NAME: Moananagh Bridge
COMPOSITION: Four-arch hump-back road bridge over river Inagh, built c. 1820.  Rubble stone walls with cut-stone rusticated voussoirs and stepped V-cutwaters.

NAME: Saint Columba's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Roman Catholic church, date 1846, with four-bay side elevation, gabled porch to front and lean-to sacristy to side.  Pitched slate roof with rendered bellcote, pinnacles, cut-stone gable copings, cast-iron rainwater goods and clay ridge cresting.  Rendered walls with render quoins, hood mouldings and inset plaque.  Lancet windows with timber Y-tracery and coloured glass.  Timber doors.  Retaining interior features, including exposed timber hammer beam roof and reredos.

NAME: Saint Tola's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1910, comprising nave gable to street front with three-stage entrance tower and spire to left hand side, six-bay side elevations and two-bay transepts.  Three-bay single-storey lean-to sacristy added to left transepts and two-bay single-storey porch added to right transept, c. 1990.  Pitched artificial slate roofs with cut-stone gable copings and cross finials.  Octagonal slate roof to sprocketted spire.  Rendered walls with cut-limestone corner buttresses.  Lancet windows with hood mouldings and leaded stained glass.  Pointed arch door opening with moulded cut-stone surround and pair of timber double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: O'Loghlen Mausoleum
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted single-bay single-storey limestone cut-stone neo-Egyptian-style mausoleum, built c. 1855, with three-bay side elevations, splayed corner piers, carved plaques, moulded cornice and finials over gables. Tomb of Sir Michael O'Loghlen, the first Catholic to be apponted Master of the Rolls.

NAME: Kelly Mausoleum
COMPOSITION: Freestanding single-bay single-storey mausoleum with memorial above, built c. 1880.  Cut-limestone walls with moulded cornice and shouldered door opening having cast-iron door.
