Memorial comprising square-profile base with stepped buttresses, pinnacles and inset plaques, having octagonal-profile shaft and conical cap above.  Cut-stone piers and walls to site with cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Saint Mary's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1870, with four-bay side elevations, single-bay single-storey sacristy to right and projecting chancel to rear.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone bellcote, gable copings, cross finial and chimneystack to sacristy.  Squared coursed rock faced stone walls with quoins, plinth course and buttresses flanking entrance.  Lancet openings with cut-stone dressings and timber sliding sash windows.  Pointed arch door opening with timber matchboard double leaf doors.  Replacement window to pointed arch opening over entrance.  Rock-faced cut-stone piers to site.

NAME: Monaleen House
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1770, with single-bay two-storey return.  Now in ruins.  Rubble stone walls with remains of roughcast render.  Cut-stone soldier arches to ground floor openings.  Brick dressings to segmental-arch first floor openings.  Remains of walled garden to site.

NAME: The Lodge
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan three-bay single and two-storey house with dormer attic, dated 1861, comprising two-bay two-storey advanced block with gabled bay to left and entrance bay to right, and having recessed single-storey bay with dormer attic to right.  Now in ruins.  Snecked stone walls with rusticated stepped plinth, red brick quoins, string courses and dressing to openings.  Chamfered cut-stone lintels to openings.  Square-headed door opening having sandstone tympanum with crest and banner.

NAME: Ballyallia Stud
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1800, originally on a U-shaped plan, with pair of two-storey returns and having six-bay two-storey servants wing to right.  Two-bay two-storey flat-roofed infill block with segmental-arched doorcase added to rear, c. 1975.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Flat roof over infill block.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Tuscan limestone doorcase.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.  Group of detached four-bay single-storey stable buildings.  Detached two-bay single-storey limestone building.  Freestanding octagonal-plan single-bay single-storey limestone ice house.  Detached L-plan two-bay single-storey gate lodge with gabled projecting bays and gabled advanced chamfered porch.  Cut-limestone piers set in curved rubble stone walls.

NAME: Nutfield Bridge
COMPOSITION: Triple-arch rubble stone hump-back road bridge over river Fergus, built c. 1800, with cut-stone voussoirs and V-cutwaters.

NAME: Saint Flannan's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1874, with four-bay side elevations having projecting porch and sacristy to right hand side.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone bellcote, gable copings and finials.  Cut-stone chimneystack to sacristy.  Dressed and coursed limestone walls with buttresses, quoins and date plaque to porch.  Lancet openings with leaded glass.  Cut-limestone moulded four-centred arch door openings with label moulding above and pair of timber double leaf doors, approached by flight of limestone steps.  Pointed arch opening over entrance with replacement fixed window.  Retaining interior features, including marble altar, parquet floor, marble memorials and timber gallery.  Four coursed cut stone piers set in rusticated stone walls.

NAME: Maghera Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1925, with five-bay side elevations, projecting sacristy to right and half-octagonal apse to rear.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone bellcote, gable copings and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Roughcast rendered walls with buttresses, cut-stone quoins and feathered copings.  Render plat band to entrance front.  Lancet openings with render block-and-start architraves and leaded glass.  Pointed arch door opening with timber panelled double leaf doors.  Rubble stone boundary walls to site with rendered gate piers and wrought-iron gates.

Detached T-plan four-bay single-storey former national school, dated 1929, comprising gabled two-bay central projection flanked by recessed end bays.  Now in use a house.  Pitched slate roof with brick chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with date plaque to projecting gable.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.  Rendered piers and iron gates set in roughcast rendered boundary walls.

Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1860, with three-bay side elevations and two-bay single-storey sacristy to left.  Pitched slate roof with ridge crestings and cross finials.  Rendered walls.  Lancet openings with pivot windows and Y-tracery.  Blind arches flanking entrance with tripartite lancets above, repeating in miniature to apex.  Blind tympanum over timber matchboard door.  Retaining interior features including exposed timber roof beams, pierced timber frieze, carved reredos, panelled timber altar and granite font.  Freestanding belfry to site.

NAME: Scariff Community Council
COMPOSITION: Freestanding polygonal-plan single-bay single-storey former market weigh house, built c. 1855, now in use as community centre.  Hipped artificial slate roof with aluminium rainwater goods.  Snecked sandstone walls with cut-limestone quoins.  Cut-limestone block-and-start dressings to openings with lintels channelled to represent voussoirs and keystones.  Replacement fittings to openings.  Coved ceiling and flagged floor to interior.  Rubble stone boundary walls and weighbridge to site.

NAME: Scariff Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch road bridge over river Scariff, built c. 1860, with irregular coursed limestone walls having bull nosed copings and cut-stone voussoirs.

NAME: The Harbour Bar
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1870, with two-bay two-storey return.  Render pubfront inserted to ground floor, c. 1930.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Pebbledashed walls to ground floor with render fluted end pilasters and string course between floors.  Rendered walls to first floor with honey comb render quoins.  Shopfront comprising pilasters flanking openings with fascia, consoles and moulded cornice above.  Timber window and timber panelled double leaf door with overlight and limestone steps to shopfront.  Shouldered render architrave to timber panelled door leading to residential accommodation. Formerly "W. Bolton", licence in this name in light over door.

NAME: Sacred Heart of Jesus Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1830, with four-bay side elevations, single-bay transepts and single-bay chancel.  Single-bay three-stage tower added to entrance and two-bay two-storey sacristy added to rear, c. 1890.  Pitched slate roof with cross finials.  Crenellated parapet and pyramidal copper roof to tower.  Rendered walls.  Rusticated snecked limestone walls with cut-stone string courses to tower.  Pointed arch openings with leaded glass.  Hood mouldings to ground and first floor tower openings.  Oculi to transept gables.  Pointed arch and Tudor arch door openings with timber matchboard doors.  Retaining interior features including marble altar, reredos, altar railing, mosaic to chancel walls, raked galleries and cut-stone font.  Rusticated stone piers with cast-iron gates and railings to site.

NAME: Scariff Dock
COMPOSITION: Cut-limestone quay wall, built c. 1850, with cast-iron bollards. Crane with plaque.
Freestanding two-bay six-stage rubble stone water tower, built c. 1860, with base batter, battlemented roof parapet and square-headed narrow openings.  Now in ruins.

NAME: Saint Joseph's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1870, with advanced entrance porch, five-bay side elevations and chancel to rear.  Four-bay single-storey projecting sacristy, added c. 1990.  Pitched slate roof with fish scale pattern bands, cut-stone bellcote, copings and cross finials.  Pitched artificial slate roof to sacristy.  Snecked rusticated limestone walls with stepped buttresses and octagonal corner pinnacles to entrance front.  Rendered walls to sacristy.  Pointed arch openings with cut-stone block-and-start surrounds and leaded glass.  Pointed arch door opening with timber matchboard double-leaf doors.  Retaining interior features including carved altar and reredos.  Cut-stone piers with pyramidal capping and cast-iron gate.

NAME: Brooklawn House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey former rectory, built c. 1800, with two-bay two-storey return.  Possibly incorporating fabric of earlier building.  Converted to use as private house, c. 1920.  Now also in use as guest house.  Pitched slate roofs with rendered chimneystacks and having brick chimneystack to rear.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Round-headed door opening with timber panelled door, cobweb fanlight and stone threshold.  Timber sliding sash and replacement windows with stone sills.  Retaining interior features.  Yard to rear with rubble stone boundary walls, segmental-arch opening with cut-stone voussoirs and timber gates and two-storey outbuilding.

NAME: East Clare Heritage Centre
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height church, built pre 969, by Cormac ui Cilleen.  Renovated, 1002, by Brian Boru.  Renovated and extended to rear, 1893.  Now also in use as heritage centre.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone bellcote and gable copings.  Rubble and coursed stone walls with engaged colonnettes to corner to road.  Recessed timber half glazed door with cut-stone lintel.  Replacement timber windows set splayed reveals having carved chevrons.  Stained glass window to chancel.  Retaining interior features including marble memorials, timber pulpit, pews and lectern.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers and mausolea.  Rubble stone boundary walls to site.

NAME: O'Grady's Castle
COMPOSITION: Freestanding orthogonal-plan single-bay three-stage tower with base batter, built c. 1550, now in ruins.  Parapet with string course below, formerly battlemented.  Rubble stone walls with machicolation over entrance.  Various openings including gun loops and pointed arch openings. On river bank adjacent to church built by O'Grady, Lords of territory of Hy-donghaile, noted in TCD lists of castles of Thomond and in Annals of the Four Masters (1564)

NAME: Raheen Lodge
COMPOSITION: Detached polygonal-plan single-bay single-storey former gate lodge, built c. 1820.  Two-bay two-storey return added to rear and projecting open porch added to front, c. 1985.  Now in use as private house.  Hipped slate roof with cut-stone chimneystack at apex and gablet over former entrance.  Pitched artificial slate roof to return.  Cut-limestone walls.  Timber cladding to porch addition.  Rendered walls to return.  Timber windows and doors.  Moulded limestone cut-stone piers set in rubble stone crenellated curved walls with cast-iron gates.

NAME: Our Lady of the Assumption
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1844, with three-bay side elevations having single-bay transepts.  Pitched slate roof with ashar gable finial.  Roughcast rendered walls with render quoins.  Lancet openings with leaded coloured glass and stone sills.  Cut-stone dressings to entrance gable window.  Tudor arch door opening with cut-stone dressings and timber matchboard door.  Retaining interior features.  Rendered boundary walls and wrought-iron gates to site.

NAME: Ford Edward
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house with central breakfront, built c. 1845, with single-bay single-storey lean-to return having dormer attic added to rear, c. 1960.  In use as parochial house, c. 1915.  Hipped slate roof with brick chimneystack.  Exposed rubble stone walls with cut-stone quoins and brick dressings to openings.  Cut-stone walls to breakfront.  Rendered walls to sides and rear.  Replacement fittings to square-headed window openings and segmental-arched door opening.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Saint Mary's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1826, with gabled projecting porch to entrance gable, four-bay side elevations having single-bay transepts and two-bay single-storey sacristy to rear.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone bellcote, gable copings and cross finial.  Rendered walls with render quoins and plaque to west transept wall.  Pointed arch openings with replacement windows and doors.  Retaining interior features.  Rusticated cut-stone piers and walls with cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Feakle Church of Ireland Graveyard
COMPOSITION: Graveyard to former Church of Ireland church with various grave markers and mausolea, from c. 1825 to c. 1995.  Cut-stone gate piers with wrought-iron gates and railings to site.  Church of Ireland church, built 1823, now demolished.

NAME: Scarriff Union Workhouse
COMPOSITION: Group of detached cut-stone sandstone buildings originally part of Scarriff Union Workhouse complex, built c. 1845.  Two-bay single-storey lodge, now in use as outbuilding.  Gable-fronted single-bay two-storey building, now in ruins.  Section of boundary wall and entrance piers with wall-mounted cast-iron post box addition.  Pitched slate roofs with cut-stone chimneystacks, cut-stone gable copings and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Coursed cut-stone sandstone walls.  Pointed arch door openings and square-headed window openings with cut-stone architraves, some retaining diamond paned windows, some now blocked.

NAME: Raheen Estate
COMPOSITION: Remains of Raheen Estate, built c. 1850.  Detached three-bay single-storey coursed sandstone gate lodge with single-bay open internal porch to centre, hipped slate roof, cut-stone chimneystack, chamfered corners and timber sliding sash windows.  Detached five-bay two-storey rubble stone-built stable building with pitched slate roof and elliptical-headed integral carriageway.  Freestanding furnace, now in ruins.  Carved and cut-stone channelled piers with consoles and moulded capping set in crenellated coursed stone boundary walls.  Raheen House now demolished.

NAME: Fulford House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1840, with single-bay single-storey flat-roofed projecting porch to centre.  Formerly in use as RIC barracks.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and moulded eaves course.  Pebbledashed walls with render plat bands and having moulded render cornice and frieze to porch.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber panelled door.  Retaining interior features.  Garage added, c. 1985, to right hand side.  Wrought-iron gates set in rendered boundary walls to site.

NAME: Atlantic Lodge
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey former coastguard station, built c. 1870, with advanced end bay having full-height canted bay window to left and three-bay single-storey return to rear.  Now in use as private house.  Glazed porch added to entrance.  Pitched and hipped slate roofs with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with string courses to projecting bay.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Billow Ville
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820, with full-height bowed section to centre.  Porch added, c. 1995.  Formerly in use as hotel, now in use as holiday accommodation for a religious order.  Pitched artificial slate with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls.  Replacement fittings to openings.  Rubble stone boundary walls with cobble style copings.

NAME: Mother MacAuley House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1830, with three-bay central breakfront having single-bay single-storey flat-roofed projecting porch to centre and single-bay two-storey return.  Twenty-seven-bay single-storey flat-roofed wing added to right and three-bay single-storey extension, added c. 1940.  Owned by religious order since 1929.  Now in use as holiday accommodation.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered belfry with cross finial.  Rendered walls with render quoins and label mouldings over openings.  Moulded cornice to porch.  Replacement fittings to openings.  Curved rendered boundary walls with rendered piers and decorative timber gates.

NAME: Stella Maris
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey house, built c. 1870, with recessed central bay.  Three-bay two-storey recessed wing added to right and three-bay single-storey flat-roofed return added, c. 1920.  Hipped artificial slate with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls.  Replacement windows.  Timber panelled door with sidelights and overlight.  Retaining interior shutters.  Rubble stone boundary walls with carved monolithic gate piers to site.

NAME: Bealaclugga Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch limestone cut-stone road bridge over river, built 1824, with lancet arch, cut-stone abutments, voussoirs, piers and parapet walls having mock loopholes.

NAME: Christ Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Church of Ireland church, dated 1927, with two-stage tower and spire having attached gabled porch to left hand side, two-bay side elevations having projecting sacristy and polygonal apse to right hand side.  Pitched and hipped clay red tile roof with cut-stone copings and finial.  Concrete broach spire.  Roughcast rendered walls with stepped buttresses.  Plat band and inscribed plaque to tower.  Pointed arch openings with render architraves, and leaded and stained glass.  Timber matchboard door.

NAME: The Retreat
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay single-storey house, built c. 1825, with gabled projecting porch and three-bay return having single-bay single-storey over part-raised basement battlemented tower with base batter and corner turret.  Arranged on an L-shaped plan about a courtyard.  Originally thatched, re-roofed c. 1920, now derelict.  Pitched slate roof with concrete ridge tiles.  Pyramidal slate roof set behind rendered battlemented parapet to tower.  Crenellated parapet to turret.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Square-headed openings.  Blocked openings to base of tower, with lancet openings to turret.  Gateway to site, comprising four circular-profile piers with battlemented cappings, battlemented boundary walls and wrought-iron gate.

NAME: Stackpoole's Bridge (South)
COMPOSITION: Double-arch humpback road bridge over river, built c. 1820, with V-cutwaters and pedestrian refuge.  Coursed rubble stone walls with cut-stone copings and voussoirs.
Single-arch humpback stone road bridge over river, built c. 1840, with cut-stone voussoirs.

NAME: Aghy Bridge
COMPOSITION: Double-arch rubble stone built road bridge over river, built c. 1800, with V-cutwaters and cut-stone voussoirs.

NAME: Doonsallagh Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch coursed stone road bridge over river, built c. 1820, with cut-stone voussoirs and inscribed benchmark.

NAME: Honan's Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch rubble stone road bridge over river, dated 1872, with cut-stone copings and inscribed plaque.

NAME: Church of Immaculate Conception
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1858, with five-bay elevation having central door opening.  Pitched artificial slate roof.  Pebbledashed walls with cut-stone quoins and niche with statue over entrance door.  Lancet openings with leaded coloured glass windows and cut-stone dressings.  Pseudo four-centred arch door opening with cut-stone dressings, timber matchboard double leaf doors and etched glass fanlight.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-stone gate piers set in rendered boundary walls to site.  Grotto and belfry to rear.

NAME: Inagh Bridge
COMPOSITION: Triple-arch rubble stone road bridge over river Inagh, built c. 1790, with cut-stone V-cutwaters and voussoirs.

NAME: Saint Michael's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1860, with five-bay side elevation and half-octagonal apse to rear.  Pitched and hipped slate roof with bands of red slate, concrete ridge crestings, cross finial and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Snecked stone walls with cut-stone plinths, stepped buttresses and tripartite blind niches at apex.  Lancet openings with cut-stone dressings and leaded coloured glass.  Pointed arch door opening with pair of timber double leaf doors, fanlight, flanking lancet side lights, and with rose window above.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Driminure Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch rubble stone road bridge over river, dated 1846, with cut-stone voussoirs, piers and copings.

NAME: Friars Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch rubble stone road bridge over river, dated 1846, with cut-stone voussoirs, piers and coping.

NAME: Bushy Park House
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan three-bay two-storey over part-raised basement former house, built c. 1820, with recessed central entrance bay approached by flight of steps and two-bay two-storey return with single-bay single-storey lean-to end bay.  Now in use as health centre.  Hipped artificial slate roof with sprocketted eaves and rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with render quoins.  Channelled render walls to basement.  Render architraves to timber sliding sash windows.  Segmental-arch door opening with timber panelled double leaf doors flanked by sidelights with cobweb fanlight above.  Retaining interior features.  Detached single-bay two-storey rubble stone summer house, with single-bay single-storey projecting glazed porch added to front, c. 1990.  Cut-stone stone gate piers to site with wrought-iron double leaf gates.

NAME: Claureen Bridge
COMPOSITION: Triple-arch rubble stone road bridge over river, built c. 1820, with cut-stone V-cutwaters and voussoirs.

NAME: Saint Joseph's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1842, with three-bay side elevations.  Projecting porch added to entrance and sacristy added to rear, 1969.  Pitched artificial slate with metal cross finials.  Roughcast rendered walls with cut-stone quoins.  Lancet opening with cut-stone surrounds and leaded glass.  Timber doors.  Retaining interior features.   Brass plaque in porch : "This porch has been erected / as a memorial to the late Mike McTigue / World light heavyeight champion boxer / 1923-25  by his friends in the USA / born in Kilnamona 1892 died in New York 1966 /R.I.P. / Dec. 1969".  Cast-iron belfry to site.  Cut-stone gate piers set in rubble stone crenellated boundary walls.

NAME: Inch Bridge
COMPOSITION: Five-arch rubble stone road bridge over river, built c. 1830, with cut-stone voussoirs and keystones.

NAME: Cahercalla House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey former house, built c. 1810, with pedimented central breakfront having flat-roofed projecting porch.  Now in use as hospital.  Fourteen-bay three-storey flat-roofed wing added to left hand side and six-bay two-storey wing added to right hand side, 1953.  Hipped artificial slate roof with eaves consoles and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with render quoins, render architraves, consoled entablatures over ground floor opening and moulded eaves course.  Moulded cornice and label mouldings over round-headed openings to porch.  Timber sliding sash windows and timber panelled door.  Detached three-bay single-storey outbuilding to site.

NAME: Our Lady's Hospital
COMPOSITION: Detached symmetrical-plan thirty-three-bay three-storey over basement former mental asylum, completed 1868, comprising five-bay projecting central block with single-bay four-stage advanced central tower, flanked by recessed fourteen-bay wings with three-bay projecting blocks and three-bay projecting end blocks, having single-bay four-stage towers to rear.  Pair of five-bay two-storey returns with dormer attics having two-storey half-octagonal projecting end bays added to rear, c. 1900.  Now in use as hospital.  Hipped slate roofs with cut-stone dentillated eaves courses.  Snecked limestone walls with cut-stone quoins, plinth and eaves band.  Channelled limestone with string course above to ground floor breakfront.  Segment-arched openings with cut-stone architraves and sills and timber sliding sash windows.  Tuscan columns and pilasters with entablature flanking timber glazed door having overlight and sidelights.  Detached two-bay single-storey rusticated limestone gate lodge with single-bay canted bay window to left and segmental-headed door opening to right.  Detached T-plan five-bay double-height chapel, built c. 1930.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-limestone gate piers.  Designed by Fogerty and Adair.

NAME: Ballymacquiggan Bridge
COMPOSITION: Double-arch limestone road bridge over river, built c. 1830, with cut-stone voussoirs and stile incorporated in wall.  Partly reconstructed, c. 1990, retaining original materials.

NAME: Toonagh House
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1800.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Roughcast rendered walls with render quoins and architraves.  Replacement windows and door.  Detached single-bay single-storey gable-fronted rubble stone dovecote with segmental-headed door opening, possibly formerly in use as mill, now in ruins.  Single-arch cut-stone bridge over stream with cut-stone voussoirs and pyramidal copings.

NAME: Moyriesk House
COMPOSITION: Remains of detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1790, originally part of larger building, now derelict and in use as outbuilding.  Hipped slate roof with brick chimneystacks and dentillated eaves course.  Hipped slate roof to former entrance canopy.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls to ground floor and red brick English garden bond walls to first floor with string courses and cut-stone quoins.  Remains of timber sliding sash windows, metal sheeting and boarding to openings.

NAME: Kilbreckam Silver Mines
COMPOSITION: Remains of silver mines, in use c. 1775, disused, pre-1921.  Detached single-bay three-storey rubble stone building, now in ruins.  Freestanding circular-profile rubble stone chimney with red brick dressings, now overgrown.

NAME: Tyredagh Spa House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey house with dormer attic, built 1879, with gabled projecting central entrance bay.  Gable-fronted single-bay single-storey extension with dormer attic added to right hand side, c. 1990.  Pitched slate roof with timber finials, red brick chimneystacks, timber bargeboard to gable and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Pitched artificial slate to extension.  Rendered walls.  Replacement uPVC windows.  Round-headed door opening with timber panelled door having glazed panels and plain fanlight.  Wrought-iron gate and piers set in rubble stone walls.

NAME: Derrymore House
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1800.  Single-bay two-storey flat-roofed return, added c. 1970.  Pitched slate roof with three rendered chimneystacks.  Pebbledashed walls to first floor, rendered walls to ground floor with rendered plat bands.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Replacement timber panelled door with multiple pane sidelight.  Rendered piers with wrought-iron gates to garden.  Cut-stone stone piers set in rendered boundary walls with cast-iron gates.

NAME: Cullan Castle
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey over basement house, dated 1782, with central breakfront and three-bay full-height bowed section to rear elevation.  Now in ruins.  Roof no longer in existence.  Dressed stone walls with carved plaque to breakfront and string course between floors.  Round-headed door opening with pilasters flanking opening, having cornice and archivolt above, now blocked.  Tripartite window opening comprising moulded architrave with columns forming mullions.  Rendered brick block-and-start surrounds to window openings.  Rubble stone former Roman Catholic chapel with lancet-arched openings, now in ruins.  Detached L-plan two-bay single-storey gate lodge with dormer attic, now derelict. Freestanding gazebo with a stepped base, now in ruins.

NAME: Cloonteen House
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay single- and two-storey former estate worker's house with dormer attic, built c. 1875, comprising two-bay two-storey block with two-bay single-storey wing having dormer attic.  Now in use as private house.  Pitched slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods, rendered and red brick chimneystacks and gabled dormer.  Rendered walls with inscribed plaque.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber panelled door.  Detached multiple-bay single-storey rubble stone outbuilding with round-headed integral carriage arches, built c. 1875.  Detached three-bay single-storey former gate lodge with gabled projecting porch to centre, c. 1890, now in use as private house.  Cut-stone gate piers to site.

NAME: Derrymore House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey cut-limestone gate lodge with prostyle tetrastyle pedimented Doric portico, built c. 1820, now vacant.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone chimneystack.  Cut-limestone walls to front with carved detail to portico.  Dressed stone walls to side.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Door opening now blocked.  Cut-stone piers and boundary walls to site.

NAME: Derrymore House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820, incorporating fabric of earlier building, c. 1650.  Originally the servants' wings of larger house, demolished 1937.  Four-bay single-storey lean-to projecting bay with pair of internal porches, added c. 1985.  Pitched slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods and four red brick chimneystacks.  Pitched artificial slate roof to extension.  Rubble stone and rendered walls.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber casement windows to extension.  Glazed timber panelled doors.  Detached sixteen-bay two-storey rubble stone outbuilding, c. 1820, with pair of segmental-headed integral carriageways and single-bay single-storey crenellated connecting screen wall to left.  Detached eight-bay two-storey coursed stone barrel-roofed outbuilding, c. 1820, with segmental-headed integral carriageway.

NAME: Saint Mary's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1840, with single-bay nave and single-bay transepts.  Pitched slate roof with metal cross finial and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with inset fonts.  Pointed arch openings with timber sliding sash windows.  Timber matchboard doors.  Retaining interior features.  Rusticated concrete block boundary walls.

NAME: Tinerana House
COMPOSITION: Detached eight-bay two-storey over basement house with dormer attic, built c. 1860 by the Purdon family, with two-bay projecting back to left hand side and conservatory to right hand side.  Incorporating fabric of earlier building.  Now also in use as guesthouse.  Hipped skirt roof with eaves modillions, dormer windows, cut-stone sandstone chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Exposed sandstone walls with stringcourses.  Cut-stone sandstone doorcase with moulded chamfered reveals, double archivolts above, and pilasters retain springing stones of un-built portico.  Timber sliding sash windows, elongated to light staircase.  Timber casement windows to dormers.  Retaining interior features.

Freestanding Church of Ireland church, built c. 1860, comprising three-bay nave with lean-to vestry and three-stage entrance tower.  Built by the Purdon family.  Rooflights added, c. 1985, to accommodate use as private house.  Pitched slate roof with rendered chimneystack, cast-iron rainwater goods and cut-stone gable copings.  Castellations and pinnacles to tower.  Exposed stone walls with quoins to nave and having string courses and chamfered corner pilasters to tower.  Pointed arch openings with cut-stone architraves and leaded windows.  Timber matchboard door.  Octagonal-profile font to front.  Graveyard to site.

NAME: Saint Mary's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1844, with four-bay side elevations having two-bay transepts with gabled projecting porches.  Pitched artificial slate roof.  Rendered walls.  Lancet openings with replacement uPVC windows.  Retaining interior features.  Concrete brick walls and piers added to site, c. 1970.

NAME: Blessed Virgin Mary, Star of the Sea Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan Hiberno-Romanesque style Roman Catholic church, dated 1909, with two-bay transepts, round tower, porch and semi-circular-plan apse to right hand side.  Recessed single-bay added to left.  Pitched slate roof with carved eaves brackets and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Conical cut-stone stone roof to tower.  Half conical roof to apse.  Dressed stone walls with canted buttresses.  String course and plaque to tower.  Round-headed window openings.  Oculi to gables.  Pedimented round-headed doorcase to base of tower, with painted columns and timber matchboard door.  Retaining interior features.  Rubble stone boundary walls.  Church built in 1909 to commemorate wreck of French vessel Leon XIII in 1907 and the rescue of its crew by local men.  Bell of ship in altar.

NAME: Church of the Most Holy Redeemer
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1865, with four-bay side elevations.  Projecting entrance porch and two-bay single-storey sacristy added to right, 1978.  Pitched artificial slate roof with sheeted timber soffits and aluminium rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with buttresses to east elevation.  Pointed openings with timber traceried windows and timber panelled double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Graveyard and freestanding belfry to site.

NAME: Saint John's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1844, with three-bay side elevations having single-bay transepts.  Single-bay two-storey gabled projecting porch to front having concrete canopy, added, c. 1965.  Pitched artificial slate roof with sheeted eaves and aluminium rainwater goods.  Pebbledashed walls.  Lancet openings with leaded glass and timber matchboard doors.  Retaining interior features.  Cast-iron belfry to site.  Rubble stone crenellated boundary walls.

NAME: Saint John the Baptist's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1857 with stepped central breakfront and three-bay side elevations having single-bay transepts.  Three-bay single-storey sacristy, added 1991.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cross finial.  Pebbledashed walls with lined-and-ruled render to breakfront.  Lancet openings with leaded glass and timber matchboard double-leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Detached two-bay single-storey rubble stone coach house with segmental-headed carriageway, now derelict.  Cut-stone piers and wrought-iron gates with crenellated boundary walls.

NAME: Teermaclane House
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1800, now in ruins.  Roof missing with brick eaves course.  Exposed coursed stone walls with cut-stone quoins and plinth.  Serlian door opening with cut-limestone dressings.  Attached single-bay single-storey rubble stone outbuilding to site.  Cut-stone architraves and keystones to window openings.

NAME: Barntick House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, dated 1661, and renovated c. 1740.  Hipped slate roof with red brick chimneystacks.  Roughcast rendered walls with string course between ground and first floors and moulded eaves course.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Carved limestone door surround comprising shouldered surround with entablature above, approached by flight of limestone steps.  Timber panelled double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Attached single-bay single-storey outbuilding to right.  Date plaque from house moved to outbuilding.  Rendered gate piers to site with wrought-iron railings.

NAME: Buncraggy House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1780, with single-bay single-storey projecting porch, single-bay full-height canted bay windows and four-bay two-storey lower return to rear.  Hipped slate roof with brick chimneystacks.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Red brick walls to right hand side bay window.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Detached five-bay two-storey outbuilding with segmental-headed door opening having cut-stone surround and keystone.  Detached three-bay single-storey gate lodge with tripartite window openings, now derelict.  Cut-stone piers with cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Church of Saint Peter and Saint Paul
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1839, comprising gable-fronted nave with four-bay side elevations and single-bay transepts.  Triple gable-fronted blocks added to front, 1986, comprising glazed central atrium block flanked by rendered blocks.  Gable-fronted porches added to transepts, 1986.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone bellcote.  Rendered walls with render quoins.  Lancet openings with cut-stone block-and-start architraves and leaded glass.  Segmental-arched former door opening with label moulding.  Retaining interior features.  Rendered piers with pyramidal copings set in rubble stone wall.

NAME: Newhall House
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey red brick house, built c. 1765, with three-bay full-height balustraded canted central projection, single-bay full-height bow windows to side elevations and eight-bay two- and three-storey lower wing to rear.  Design attributed to architect Francis Bindon.  Possibly incorporating fabric of earlier building, c. 1650.  Hipped slate roof to main block, conical roofs to side bows and pitched roof to rear with cut-stone eaves course, brick chimneystacks, and balustrade to canted central projection.  Flemish bond brick walls with cut-stone string course and brick panels over first floor windows.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Carved limestone door surround comprising shouldered architrave with pediment above.  Timber panelled door.  Retaining interior features.  Pair of detached single-bay single-storey gate lodges with round-headed niches, lancet-arch openings and diagonal corner piers to site, now derelict.  Cut-stone piers with cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Thomond Villas
COMPOSITION: Group of former army barracks buildings, built c. 1790, now disused or in use as private dwellings.  Detached L-plan six-bay three-storey block with three-bay gabled projection to right, renovated c. 1975.  Detached four-bay three-storey rubble stone block with cut-stone quoins, red brick relieving arches and three-bay side elevations, renovated, c. 1975.  Detached five-bay three-storey block retaining original fenestration, now derelict.  Detached ten-bay three-storey rubble stone officers' building retaining original fenestration, cut-stone quoins, red brick relieving arches and pair of segmental-headed door openings having fanlights, now derelict.  Pitched roof with artificial slate to restored blocks and natural slate to derelict blocks with red brick and rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with render quoins to restored blocks.  Rubble stone walls to derelict blocks.  Red brick block-and-start surrounds to timber sliding sash windows of derelict blocks.  Round-headed door openings with timber panelled doors, fanlights and sidelights to derelict blocks.  Replacement windows and doors to restored blocks.

NAME: Carnelly House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey over basement red brick house, built c. 1750.  Design attributed to architect Francis Bindon.  Three-bay two-storey recessed wing added to right hand side, c. 1840.  Hipped slate roof with brick chimneystacks and cut-stone eaves course.  Pitched slate roof to extension.  Brick walls with cut-stone plat bands, plinth and quoins.  Rendered walls to side.  Carved limestone Serlian doorcase with timber panelled door, sidelights and fanlight, approached by flight of limestone steps.  Timber sliding sash and casement windows set in cut-stone architraves with keystones.  Retaining interior features.  Detached three-bay single-storey double-pile red brick gate lodge with single-bay gabled projecting central bay having elliptical-headed door opening and bracketed eaves.  Cut-stone piers with cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Glenard House
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1810, with single-bay two-storey return.  Possibly originally a rectory.  Single-bay single-storey gabled projecting glazed porch added to centre, c. 1920.  Single-bay two-storey lean-to, added c. 1955.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Pitched roof to porch with finial and decorative timber bargeboards.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Tripartite timber sliding sash and replacement casement windows.  Retaining interior features.  Detached four-bay single-storey gate lodge to site.  Cut-stone stone gate piers set in curved walls.  Associated farm buildings to rear.

NAME: Manus House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1810, with three-bay two-storey return to rear.  Glazed porch with carved bargeboards and finial added to entrance.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Red brick walls to front elevation.  Rubble stone walls with red brick dressings to openings to return.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Round-headed door opening with radial fanlight and timber panelled door.  Retaining interior shutters.  Detached L-plan twenty-two-bay single-storey rubble stone-built stable complex with segmental-headed carriageways and bellcote to site.

NAME: Latoon Bridge
COMPOSITION: Triple-arch rubble stone hump-back road bridge over river, built c. 1810, with cut-stone voussoirs, keystones and V-cutwaters. Now bypassed by new road and bridge.

NAME: Ardsollus Station (former)
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey former railway station with dormer attic, built 1859, having gabled projecting bays flanking entrance.  Now in use as house.  Single-bay single-storey flat-roofed bay added to left, three-bay single-storey flat-roofed recessed wing added to right and single-bay single-storey flat-roofed projecting porch added to front with lancet door opening, c. 1990.  Pitched slate roof with rusticated concrete chimneystack.  Dormer windows added to rear.  Snecked limestone walls with cut-stone quoins.  Painted brick reveals to replacement timber windows.  Timber matchboard door.  Blind loops to gables.  Rubble stone boundary walls and gate piers to site.

NAME: Ballyhannon House
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820, with recessed single-bay two-storey wing to right hand side.  Hipped slate roof with dentilated eaves and rendered chimneystacks.  Roughcast rendered walls with render quoins.  Segmental-arched door opening with timber panelled door, flanking sidelights and radial fanlight.  Timber panelled door.  Retaining interior shutters.  Group of detached two-bay single-storey outbuildings to site.  Cut-stone piers with moulded capping having cast-iron gates and railings.
Freestanding limestone cut-stone milestone with inscription, dated 1828.

NAME: Quin Bridge
COMPOSITION: Triple-arch rubble stone hump-back road bridge over river, built c. 1800, with cut-stone voussoirs, keystones and V-cutwaters.  Rubble stone parapets, haunches and abutments with cut-stone parapet copings.  Flights of cut stone steps leading to river bank.

NAME: Saint Finghin's Church
COMPOSITION: Remains of detached four-bay single-storey rubble stone single-cell  church, dated 1278, with single-bay three-stage crenellated tower to left gable.  Now in ruins.   Rebuilt after destruction of earlier church by Thomas de Clare.  Cut-limestone gate piers with string courses, copings and cast-iron gates.

NAME: Dromoland Castle
COMPOSITION: Detached six-bay two-storey Gothic Revival former country house, built c.1835, designed by the English architects James Pain (1779-1877) and his brother George Richard. Single-bay two-storey advanced bay to left having single-bay full-height canted bay windows, projecting porch and circular-plan single-bay three-stage tower to right.  Six-bay side elevations having square-plan two-bay four-stage tower to left.  Six-bay three-storey return to rear having three-bay single-storey projecting porch with single-bay two-storey polygonal turret above, approached by flight of steps.  Renovated, 1962, to accommodate use as hotel.  Crenellated roof parapets with machicolations to towers and cut-stone octagonal chimneystacks with domed cappings.  Cut-limestone walls with rusticated plinth, carved bartizans, finials, crests, corbels and moulded string courses. Single and paired timber sliding sash windows with mullions, transoms and label mouldings.  Tudor arch door openings with timber panelled double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Detached multiple-bay two-storey outbuilding.  Detached four-bay single-storey gate lodge with pedimented prostyle tetrastyle Doric portico.  Folly and other landscape features to site.  Gateway of Lemanagh Castle, c. 1600, set in walled garden.  Cut-limestone gate piers with fluted friezes and cast-iron gates.  Original early 18th. century house demolished, c. 1826, by Sir Edward O'Brien.  Sold in 1962 by 16th Lord Inchiquin.

NAME: Knappogue Castle
COMPOSITION: Freestanding square-plan four-bay three-stage tower house with base batter, built c. 1465.  Seven-bay single-storey wing with two-bay advanced bay, square-plan single-bay three-stage tower to left and two-bay two-storey bay to right, remodelled 1855 by architects James Pain (1779-1877) and his brother George Richard.  Renovated, 1969, to accommodate use as restaurant and private residence.  Pitched roof with castellations and machicolated to tower.  Rubble stone walls to tower.  Rock-faced cut-stone to extensions with Masonic symbols to keystones and carved plaques.  Glazed gun loops and grouped narrow openings to tower.  Cut-stone architraves with label mouldings and timber sliding sash windows to extensions.  Retaining interior features.  Detached two-bay single-storey gate lodge, built c. 1855.  Limestone cut-stone pointed arch gateway with battlemented parapet having machicolation.

NAME: Dromoland Belvedere
COMPOSITION: Freestanding octagonal-plan single-bay double-height over part-raised basement belvedere, built c. 1740, with obelisk to apex.  Cut-limestone roof with moulded blocked course and cornice.  Roughcast rendered walls over rubble stone construction, with cut-stone string courses and blind panels over openings.  Red brick dressings to openings.  Yellow brick groin vaulted basement, brick cross ribbed vaulting to main chamber and chimney flue to interior.  Four triangular-plan mounds form star-shaped platform with flight of cut-stone steps leading to entrance.

NAME: Knappogue Castle
COMPOSITION: Gateway, built c. 1840, comprising pair of tapered cut-limestone panelled piers with inscriptions and carved hands, having moulded cornice, domed cappings and cast-iron gates.  Pier inscriptions act as mile stones.  Set in rubble stone boundary walls with square-headed pedestrian gateway to left.

NAME: Manus South House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1840, with single-bay single-storey gabled projecting glazed porch to centre and single-bay single-storey recessed bay to right.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Timber bargeboards and finial to porch.  Pebbledashed walls with render quoins.  Precast plaster pediments additions to ground floor window openings.  Replacement uPVC windows.  Replacement glazed timber panelled door.  Detached four-bay two-storey outbuilding with cut-stone bellcote.  Cut-stone piers with cast-iron gates.

NAME: Kilkishen Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Church of Ireland church, dated 1811, comprising two-bay nave with single-bay three-stage crenellated entrance tower.  Now disused.  Pitched slate roof.  Rubble stone walls with corner buttresses to nave.  Cut-limestone walls with string course, crenellations, pinnacles and plaque to tower.  Pointed arch openings with cut-stone architraves and cast-iron quarry glazing.  Pointed arch and Tudor arch openings with label mouldings to tower.  Pointed arch door opening with timber matchboard doors having wrought-iron strap hinges.

NAME: Kilkishen House
COMPOSITION: Gateway, built c. 1810, comprising four cut-limestone panelled piers with segmental copings, inset carved plaques and cast-iron gates and railings.  Set in curved cut-limestone walls.

NAME: Belvoir Estate
COMPOSITION: Remains of detached five-bay two-storey over basement Gothic Revival house with dormer attic, built c. 1820, having single-bay single-storey flat-roofed projecting porch to centre.  Burnt, 1880, now in ruins.  Roof now missing, retaining central gablet.  Irregularly coursed sandstone walls with rusticated limestone quoins.  Corner piers with pinnacles to porch.  Limestone sills, block-and-start surrounds and label mouldings to openings.  L-plan three-bay single-storey crenellated screen wall with lancet openings and gable between house and chapel.  Detached three-bay single-storey rubble stone-built single-cell Lady's Chapel, built 1862-1863.  Pitched slate roof with rooflights, cast-iron crestings and cut-stone bellcote.  Irregularly coursed cut-stone sandstone walls with limestone quoins and stepped buttresses.  Lancet openings with cut-stone dressings and timber stained glass windows.  Timber panelled door.  Group of detached buildings set around courtyard, built c. 1840, comprising nine-bay two-storey stable building with half-dormer attic, three-bay two-storey house and single-bay double-height building with elliptical-headed integral carriageway.  Gateway, built c. 1840, comprising four cut-stone piers with cornices and pyramidal cappings set in curved walls having stile.

Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted double-height Gothic Revival Roman Catholic church, built c. 1850, with three-bay side elevations having single-bay transepts.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone bellcote, pinnacles, finials and having chimneystack to sacristy.  Roughcast rendered walls with cut-stone quoins, plat band and panel to gable.  Lancet openings with replacement uPVC windows.  Leaded coloured glass to entrance gable.  Tudor arch opening with label mouldings and timber matchboard double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers.  Cut-stone piers with cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Hurdelston House
COMPOSITION: Detached T-plan four-bay two-storey over part-raised basement house, dated 1871, with single-bay two-storey gabled projecting bay to left hand side having full-height canted bay window, flat-roofed limestone cut-stone Gothic Revival projecting porch, single-bay full-height canted bay window to side elevations and single-bay two-storey return.  Pitched slate roofs with limestone eaves corbels and chimneystacks.  Crenellated cut-stone parapets to projecting bays.  Snecked cut-stone sandstone walls with rock-faced limestone quoins having drafted margins and string course between floors.  Cut-limestone entrance porch with moulded segmental-arch openings, inscribed date stone and coved eaves course.  Cut-limestone architraves to segmental-arched openings having replacement uPVC windows.  Timber panelled door with sidelights and overlight.  Retaining interior features.  Walled garden to rear.
Single-arch rubble stone road bridge over river, built c. 1820, with cut-stone voussoirs.

NAME: The Deanery
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan three-bay two-storey deanery, built c. 1825, with three-bay two-storey return.  Hipped slate roof with cut-stone chimneystacks.  Rubble sandstone walls with cut-stone quoins.  Round-headed door opening having timber pilaster doorcase, radial fanlight and timber panelled door.  Dressed stone voussoirs and brick dressings to timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.  Wrought-iron gate set in rebuilt stone piers.

NAME: Ballyvalley House
COMPOSITION: Gateway, built c. 1800, comprising four cut-stone piers with moulded cappings and ball finials set curved rendered walls having cut-stone copings.  Square-headed pedestrian gates with cut-stone dressings and keystones.  Wrought-iron gates.  Detached three-bay single-storey gate lodge, built c. 1820, to left hand side.  Hipped artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Rendered walls.  Lancet openings.

NAME: Clarisford Palace
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey over part-raised basement former Bishop's Palace, built 1771-1779, with pedimented prostyle diastyle Tuscan portico to centre.  Now in use as private house.  Reroofed c. 1875, with hipped slate roof, dentilated eaves and rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with pilasters flanking door sidelights.  Timber sliding sash windows, set in tripartite arrangement with continuous sill to centre first floor.  Timber panelled half glazed door with timber cobweb fanlight, approached by flight of curved steps with wrought-iron railings.  Retaining interior shutters.  Detached six-bay two-storey rubble stone-built outbuilding.  Cast-iron piers with cast-iron gates.

NAME: The Sacred Heart Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Romanesque Revival Roman Catholic church, dated 1909, with five-bay side elevations having two-bay single-storey sacristy to left and single-bay chancel to rear.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone gable copings and bellcote.  Pebbledashed walls with inscribed date plaque over entrance.  Round-headed openings with render block-and-start surrounds, label mouldings and leaded glass windows.  Round-headed door opening with columns and timber matchboard double leaf doors having strap hinges, flanked by round-headed windows with continuous label mouldings above.  Round-headed openings above entrance with rose window flanked columns having stepped sill and label mouldings above and below.  Retaining interior features including sheeted timber ceiling, braced timber trusses on cut stone corbels, round head chancel arch, marble columns to altar and plate tracery to chancel window.  Channelled render gate piers with semi-cylindrical copings and wrought-iron gates set in rubble stone boundary walls.  Graveyard to site.

NAME: Ross House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1780, with attached seven-bay two-storey outbuilding to rear.  Hipped slate roofs with rendered chimneystacks and wide eaves.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.  Timber doorcase, comprising entablature with bosses on fluted frieze having dentils and panelled pilasters flanking timber panelled door.  Lunettes and Oeil de Boeuf to rear with timber glazing bars. Segmental-arch carriage opening and bellcote to outbuilding.  Detached two-bay single-storey gate lodge, now derelict.  Rusticated cut-stone piers with wrought-iron gates.
Double-arch rubble stone road bridge over river, built c. 1850, with cut-stone voussoirs and V-cutwaters.

NAME: Saint Senan's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1870, with five-bay side elevations having projecting confessionals.  Three-bay single-storey flat-roofed porch added to front and single-bay single-storey flat-roofed sacristy added to rear, 1954.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone gable copings, pebbledashed bellcote and cross finials.  Pebbledashed walls.  Pointed arch openings with leaded glass timber frame windows.  Retaining interior features including exposed braced roof timbers on stone corbels, carved stone altar with high relief carvings and marble columns, raked choir gallery with timber balustrade and marble wall mounted memorials.  Cut-stone piers with wrought-iron gates set in rubble stone walls.

NAME: Doonbeg Bridge
COMPOSITION: Six-arch rubble stone hump-back road bridge over Doonbeg river, built c. 1820, with cut-stone voussoirs, copings and V-cutwaters.

NAME: Saint Mary's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1861, with stepped central breakfront and four-bay side elevations having single-bay transepts.  Pitched artificial slate roof with timber sheeted eaves.  Roughcast rendered walls with render quoins and render detailing having inset plaques to breakfront.  Lancet openings with render surrounds and leaded glass.  Cut-stone Y-tracery to window over entrance.  Timber matchboard double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features including raked gallery, pointed arch door with cusped panelling to sacristy door, exposed painted roof timbers on stone corbels, carved white marble reredos and altar.  Roughcast rendered boundary walls.

NAME: Creegh Bridge
COMPOSITION: Triple-arch rubble stone hump-back road bridge over river Creagh, built c. 1820, with rubble stone voussoirs and V-cutwaters.

NAME: Danganella House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1800, with single-bay two-storey return.  Hipped artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Felt flat roof to extension.  Expose rubble stone and rendered walls.   Timber sliding sash windows.  Monolithic limestone gates piers with carved heart, hound and initials, having pair of double leaf wrought-iron gates.

NAME: Saint Michael's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1834, with single-bay three-stage tower to front, three-bay side elevations having two-bay transepts and flat-roofed entrance porch, with two-bay two-storey sacristy to rear.  Pitched slate roof with aluminium rainwater goods.  Copper sheeted spire and paired louvred openings to tower.  Flat roof to entrance porch.  Pebbledashed walls with blind arch having crucifix to rear gable.  Lancet openings with leaded glass windows.  Four-centred arch opening with timber matchboard doors and quatrefoils in fanlights.   Retaining interior features, including galleries to transepts, renovated organ loft, marble reredos, altar, holy water and baptismal fonts.  Snecked rubble stone boundary walls with crenellated copings.

NAME: Cornfield House
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan two-bay single-storey gate lodge, built c. 1870, with single-bay gabled projecting bay to right and single-bay recessed entrance bay to left.  Single-bay single-storey flat-roofed recessed extension added to right, c. 1970.  Double pitched slate roof with paired chamfered brick chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with cut-limestone quoins, dressings to openings and niches to gables.  Tudor arch door opening with limestone threshold and timber matchboard door.  Single and tripartite timber sliding sash windows.  Cast-iron gates with cut-limestone piers having moulded copings, set in curved snecked limestone flanking walls. Curved wall on opposite side of road echoes entrance, providing turning space.

NAME: Clondagad Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Church of Ireland church, dated 1808, with two-bay nave having curved corners and three-stage entrance tower.  Now in ruins.  Rubble stone walls.  Cut-stone string courses and copings to tower.  Lancet openings with cut-stone dressings.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers.  Mausoleum adjoining tower inscribed, ‘This monument was erected by Mr. Henry Whitestone in memory of his wife, Mrs Catherine Whitestone alias Lucas who died the 9th of December 1789 aged 61 years.'

NAME: Clondagad Glebe House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey over raised basement glebe house, built c. 1800.  Hipped slate roof with red brick chimneystacks.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills.  Timber panelled door with tripartite overlight, approached by flight of steps.  Detached two-bay single-storey outbuilding with elliptical-headed openings.  Rubble stone boundary walls and piers with wrought-iron gates.

NAME: Clondagad House
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820, with single-bay single-storey gabled projecting glazed porch to centre, single-bay single-storey lean-to conservatory to left hand side elevation and three-bay two-storey return to rear. Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and overhanging eaves having sheeted soffits.  Rendered walls.  Timber glazed porch with clay ridge tiles and carved timber bargeboards.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber panelled half-glazed double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-limestone gate piers with cast-iron double leaf gates set in rubble stone boundary walls.

NAME: Clondagad Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch coursed stone road bridge over Owenslieve river, built c. 1800, with cut-stone voussoirs and copings.

NAME: Ballycorick Bridge
COMPOSITION: Five-arch rubble stone hump-back road bridge over Owenslieve river estuary, built c. 1800, with cut-stone voussoirs, V-cutwaters and buttresses.

NAME: Ballycorick House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820, with two-bay single-storey return.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Segmental-arched door opening with radial fanlight and timber panelled door.  Attached single-bay single-storey outbuilding with attic to right.

NAME: Christ Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1860, with two-storey transepts.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone gable copings, cross finials and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Dressed limestone walls with stepped buttresses.  Lancet openings with cut-stone architraves, leaded windows and having hood mouldings over gable front openings.  Tripartite opening to chancel with stained glass window, 1872.  Timber matchboard double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-stone belfry to site.

NAME: Newmarket House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1840, with two-bay pedimented central breakfront and single-bay two-storey recessed end bay to right hand side.  Single-bay single-storey conservatory added to left hand side.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystack.  Lined-and-ruled rendered walls with cut-stone quoins, string course and with blind lunette to pediment.  Limestone cut-stone pilastered doorcase with timber panelled door flanked by sidelights having overlight with circular glazing bar above.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Detached three-bay single-storey gate lodge, now derelict.  Octagonal cut-stone gate piers with cast-iron gates, set in rubble stone walls.

Terraced four-bay two-storey former school, dated 1837, now in use as house.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone chimneystack.  Tooled snecked limestone walls with carved datestone over door.  Cut-stone architraves and chamfered lintels to timber casement windows.  Timber panelled door.

NAME: Ballycar House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey house, built c. 1810, with three-bay three-storey return and single-bay single-storey projecting porch addition to centre.  Possibly incorporating fabric of earlier building.  Hipped artificial slate roof with carved timber eaves soffits.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Replacement timber sliding sash windows.  Timber sliding sash windows to return.  Original segmental-arched doorcase to porch interior, comprising timber panelled door, flanked by sidelights with fanlight above.  Retaining interior features.  Cut-stone panelled piers with stile and wrought-iron gates.  Detached single-storey outbuildings to rear.

NAME: Our Lady of the Wells
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1820, with gabled projecting entrance porch and three-bay side elevations having single-bay transepts.  Gabled projecting porches added to transepts and two-bay single-storey sacristy with dormer attic added, c. 1985.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone bellcote.  Pebbledashed walls.  Cut limestone walls with corner buttresses to porch.  Pointed arch openings with timber Y-tracery.  Pointed arch door opening with cut-stone surrounds and timber matchboards double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Limestone cut-stone piers with moulded cappings and cast-iron piers having cast-iron gates and railings.  Hipped roofed over holy well to site.

NAME: Ballycurreen House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey over basement house, built c. 1800, with central breakfront and single-bay two-storey return to rear.  Hipped artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with render quoins and cut-stone string course between basement and first floor.  Segmental-arched door opening with limestone cut-stone pilaster doorcase, sidelights, fanlight and timber panelled door, approached by flight of steps.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Retaining interior features.  Brick segmental-arched opening set in rubble stone yard wall to rear.  Outbuildings to rear.

Detached four-bay single-storey thatched house, built c. 1860.  Pitched reed thatch roof with three red brick chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with render quoins and architraves.  Timber replacement windows and door.  Detached rubble stone outbuildings with single-pitched corrugated-iron roofs to rear.  Rendered boundary walls.

NAME: Saint Conaire's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1850, with three-bay side elevations.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cut-stone bellcote.  Pebbledashed walls with render quoins.  Lancet openings with timber Y-tracery.  Render surround, hood moulding and leaded coloured glass to entrance gable window.  Four-centred arch door opening having moulded render architrave and timber matchboard double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features including exposed roof timbers, diagonally sheeted ceiling, marble altar, timber pulpit and diagonally sheeted balustrade to organ loft.

NAME: Kilnasoolagh Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION:
Freestanding double-height Church of Ireland church, built 1816, with five-bay nave, three-stage entrance tower with spire and with single-bay single-storey vestry to rear.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods and pinnacles.  Cut-limestone spire behind castellated parapet.  Cut-stone chimneystack to vestry.  Irregularly coursed stone walls with stepped corner buttresses.  String course and render circular panel to tower.  Pointed arch openings with cut-stone surrounds, tracery and paired leaded windows.  Round-headed door opening with timber matchboard door.  Monument to Sir Donat O' Brien (d. 1717) by English sculptor William Kidwell (1662-1736).
Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers and mausolea, from c. 1870 to present.  Freestanding gable-fronted cut-stone lych gate, erected 1931, with round-headed opening and inscribed plaques.  Gateway, c. 1750, comprising cut-stone piers with pedimented round-headed opening having wrought-iron gates set in rubble stone-built boundary walls.

NAME: Walton Lodge
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1800, with two-bay two-storey return.  Single-bay two-storey extension to rear, c. 1985.  Now also in use as guesthouse.  Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Rendered walls with render quoins and surrounds to openings.  Round-headed door opening with fanlight, replacement glazed door and sidelights, approached by flight of steps.  Replacement windows.  Detached single-bay two-storey rubble stone-built outbuilding, now derelict.  Freestanding carved limestone tomb with ball finials. Freestanding carved granite 'chair' with inscriptions and crest.  Cut-stone piers with ball finials and cast-iron gates.

NAME: D'Esterres' Bridge
COMPOSITION:
Single-arch rubble stone-built humpback road bridge over river, dated 1784, with cut-stone voussoirs, cutwaters, copings and inscribed plaque.  Pair of freestanding square-plan single-bay two-storey toll houses with crow-stepped gables, built 1794, recently conserved.  Roughcast rendered walls over rubble stone construction to toll houses.   
Plaque inscribed ‘Built by Henry D'Esterres at his own expense AD 1784.'

NAME: Saint Senan's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1870, with single-bay three-stage tower and spire to right hand side, four-bay side elevations and polygonal apse to rear.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone gable copings, cross finials and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Cut-limestone broach spire.  Squared rubble stone walls with cut-stone corner buttresses.  Cut-stone plinth, string course and scalloped eaves course to tower.  Lancet openings with cut-stone dressing and cast-iron quarry glazing having horizontal pivot windows.  Pointed arch opening with timber matchboard double leaf doors, flanked by lancet windows, having continuous hood mouldings above.  Pointed arch opening to entrance gable with triple lancets and carved hood moulding.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Cloonlara Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding double-height Church of Ireland church, built c. 1815, with two-bay side elevations, single-bay single-storey additions to left and right, and single-bay three-stage entrance tower, added c. 1830.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone gable copings.  Castellations and pinnacles to tower.  Rendered walls with cut-stone eaves, plinth and quoins to nave.  Rubble stone walls to rear elevation with diagonal buttresses.  Dressed limestone walls to tower with cut-stone string courses and hood mouldings to openings.  Dressed limestone walls to vestry.  Pointed arch opening with timber panelled double leaf doors.  Lancet openings with cut-stone architraves and leaded coloured glass windows.  Timber sliding sash windows and louvres to tower openings.  Cut-stone piers with cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Cloonlara Glebe House
COMPOSITION: Detached L-plan two-bay two-storey former glebe house, built c. 1810, with three-bay two-storey return to rear having two-bay single-storey lean-to addition.  Now in use as private house.  Hipped and pitched slate roofs with red brick chimneystack.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Replacement timber windows.  Original round-headed entrance with timber doorcase having fluted frieze and fanlight now enclosed by porch.  Retaining interior features.  Lined-and-ruled rendered piers with cast-iron gates, set in rubble stone boundary walls.

NAME: Church of Mary Mother of God
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1843, with three-bay nave, single-bay transepts and sacristy to rear.  Pitched slate roof with cut-stone bellcote and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Rendered walls with pairs of inset carved stone fonts flanking entrances and inset plaque with hood moulding over entrance door.  Pointed arch openings with cut-stone architraves, hood mouldings, replacement windows and timber panelled double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features.  Wrought-iron gates set in rendered boundary wall.

NAME: Shannon Power Station
COMPOSITION: Hydroelectric power station complex, built 1925-1929, engineered by German company Siemens Schuckertwerke.  Detached twelve-bay six-storey power station with double attic built over river, having nine-bay two-storey flat-roofed projecting wing to front, two-bay advanced bay to left and four-bay side elevation.  Pitched and hipped slate roofs with concrete ridge tiles, two courses of gabled dormers, pyramidal steel-framed glazed lantern left apex, cast-iron downpipes and flat-roof to projecting wing.  Rendered and roughcast rendered walls with moulded eaves course.  Square-headed openings with slate sills, concrete mullions and multiple paned steel casement windows.  Timber panelled doors.  Interior completed c. 1940-1950.  Three turbines replaced, 1993-1997.  Attached T-plan twenty-bay three-storey flat-roofed dam/sluice house to rear with four penstock tubes.  Single-arch cast-concrete road bridge over river with pair of cast-concrete pylons, (one of four bridges over 'canal').  Pair of detached four- and six-bay three-storey flat-roofed weirs over river.  Group of detached three-bay single-storey flat-roofed outbuildings.

Triple-arch reinforced concrete hump-back road bridge over canal, built c. 1925, as part of the Ardnacrusha scheme.  Mass concrete walls with parapet copings.  Reinforced concrete pseudo three-centred arches on cast steel bearings with concrete cutwaters.

NAME: O'Brien's Bridge
COMPOSITION: Twelve-arch rubble stone road bridge over river Shannon, comprising five arches with V-cutwaters to centre, built c. 1695, six arches to right with U-cutwaters, c. 1770, and single-arch to left, c. 1925.

Detached seven-bay two-storey house, built c. 1825, with porch addition to centre.  Two-bay single-storey flanking wings, added c. 1850.  In use as Garda station in 1939.  Now in use as house.  Pitched slate roof with four red brick chimneystacks.  Hipped roofs to wings and porch.  Rendered walls with render quoins.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Timber glazed double leaf doors to porch.  Retaining interior timber shutters.  Cut-stone panelled piers with fluted friezes and pyramidal capping having cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Doonass House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1780, with single-bay recessed central bay and single-bay two-storey bowed section to left elevation.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and conical roof over bowed section.  Rendered walls.  Round-headed door opening having fanlight and timber panelled door.  Timber sliding sash windows.  Tripartite timber sliding sash windows to ground floor and to bowed section.  Cut-stone piers with fluted friezes and moulded capping having cast-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Saint Thomas's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Roman Catholic church, built c. 1980, with four-bay side elevations having projecting flat-roofed porches and sacristy.  Possibly incorporating fabric of earlier building.  Pitched artificial slate roofs.  Rendered walls.  Full-height window openings with sloping sills and leaded glass.  Half-height window with pointed arch to gable.  Glazed timber doors to porches with sidelights.  Retaining interior features.  Rendered boundary walls.  Graveyard to site with grave markers from c. 1850 to present.

NAME: Blackwater Bridge
COMPOSITION: Five-arch rubble stone hump-back road bridge over river estuary, built c. 1800, with cut-stone voussoirs and rubble stone buttresses having cut-stone quoins.

NAME: Saint Senan's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted Roman Catholic church, built 1836, with three-bay side elevations having two-bay transepts.  Pitched artificial slate roof with gable copings and cross finials.  Lined-and-ruled roughcast rendered walls with render quoins, render plat band with cross at gable apex and inset font niches to transepts.  Four-centred-arch door opening having moulded architrave and timber matchboard double leaf doors.  Lancet openings with render surrounds and leaded coloured glass.  Retaining interior features including plaster tetrastyle Ionic reredos with curved pediment and Gothic marble tabernacle.  Rendered belfry, built 1861, with carved plaque at base.

NAME: Saint Senan's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1961, with canopy over entrance, nine-bay side elevations and single-bay single-storey sacristy to right.  Pitched slate roof with deep eaves and cross finials.  Coloured concrete brick walls with roughcast rendered central panel to entrance.  Roughcast rendered side walls with coloured concrete block buttresses.  Pointed arch leaded glass windows set in pairs to side elevations, triples flanking door opening, and with timber cross mullion and transom to opening over entrance.  Timber matchboard doors.  Retaining interior features.  Concrete brick boundary wall with concrete copings.  Rendered belfry.  Graves of parish priests to site.

NAME: Inishmurry Pier
COMPOSITION: L-plan cut-limestone quay wall, built c. 1820, with cut-stone and cast-iron bollards.  Altered, c. 1970, to accommodate use as pier.

NAME: Saint Benedict's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding T-plan gable-fronted double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1865, with three-bay side elevations and single-bay transepts.  Pitched artificial slate roof with cross finials.  Concrete canopy over entrance.  Pebbledashed walls with render central panel to entrance gable.  Rendered walls to sides and rear.  Lancet openings with cut-stone block-and-start architraves, timber Y-tracery and coloured glass.  Timber matchboard double leaf doors.  Retaining interior features including marble altar, cusped sacristy door, gallery in transept and exposed roof timbers.  Attached L-plan three-bay two-storey parochial house, dated 1872, to right having gabled projecting end bay.  Rendered boundary walls.  Steel belfry to site.

NAME: Ballyleaan Water Tower
COMPOSITION: Freestanding single-bay two-storey water tower, built c. 1850, renovated, c. 1920.  Cast-iron water tank to roof.  Dressed stone walls with cut-stone quoins and dressed voussoirs to openings.  Group of detached two-bay single-storey rubble stone outbuildings arranged around courtyard, built c. 1850, now in ruins and in use as farmyard.

NAME: Shannon Airport
COMPOSITION: Shannon Airport complex comprising building and structures from several periods.  Group of detached seven-bay single-storey flat-roofed buildings, built c. 1945, with single-bay single-storey advanced bays.  Detached T-plan eleven-bay single-storey Roman Catholic chapel, built c. 1945, with prostyle tetrastyle pedimented portico, four-bay side elevations and four-bay transepts, now in use as store.  Attached four-bay two-storey flat-roofed arrival building, built c. 1960, originally detached with square-headed open arcade to ground floor.  Attached nine-bay two-storey flat-roofed International Modern-style departure building, built c. 1970, with six-bay single-storey flat-roofed projecting bay to ground floor having balcony over.  Freestanding single-bay six-stage control tower, built c. 1970, with platform to sixth floor having cantilevered tapered control room.  Runways and various outbuildings to site.

NAME: Bunratty House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey over basement former house, built c. 1805, with two-bay single-storey wing added, c. 1985.  Now in use museum and restaurant.  Hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystacks.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills, in tripartite arrangement to rear.  Round-headed door opening to centre having limestone pilaster doorcase, fanlight and timber panelled door.  Retaining interior features.  Attached twelve-bay single-storey rubble stone-built outbuildings arranged about a courtyard, with elliptical-headed carriageways and bellcote.

NAME: Bunratty Castle Hotel
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey former house, built c. 1810, with single-bay central breakfront.
